\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Microeconomics I.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Victor H.
 Aguiar 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
This version: August 2021
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Rationality and Revealed Preferences
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Revealed Preference Theory by Chambers and Echenique.
 https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/revealed-preference-theory/7637115A86AFE512E
920B6111780FEB5
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Rationality for the Consumer Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider a choice set 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{R}_{+}^{L}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $L\geq2$
\end_inset

 denotes the number of commodities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L=2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=(10kg,1.111lb)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are going to denote 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathbb{R}_{++}^{L}=P$
\end_inset

 (exclude the zero), and 
\begin_inset Formula $w\in\mathbb{R}_{+}=W$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also, when I have 2 vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1},v_{2}\in\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}v_{2}$
\end_inset

 means the inner product or 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}v_{2}=\sum_{i=1}^{L}v_{1,i}v_{2,i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Rational preference.
 We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq\subseteq X\times X$
\end_inset

 is rational whenever this is transitive and complete.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use this relation to define a demand correspondence.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Demand Correpondence.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x:P\times W\to2^{X}$
\end_inset

, and such that 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in x(p,w)$
\end_inset

 satisfies that 
\begin_inset Formula $py\leq w$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we say that a demand correspondence is rational when it is generated
 by a rational preference.
 We assume the demand correspondence is nonempty for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(p,w)$
\end_inset

 unless we state the contrary.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Rational Demand Correspondence.
 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in x(p,w)$
\end_inset

 it has to be that there is no 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in B(p,w)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $B(p,w)=\{x\in X|px\leq w\}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $z\succ y$
\end_inset

 for a rational (i.e., complete a transitive) order 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq\subseteq X\times X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

 defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succ y\iff x\succeq y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lnot y\succeq x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In real setups we do not have access to a demand correspondence, we can
 only have access to a limited dataset of prices and choices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Dataset.
 We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{K}$
\end_inset

 is a dataset if 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{K}=\{p^{k},x^{k}\}_{k=1}^{K}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $K\geq1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{k}\in X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{k}\in P$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1,\cdots,K$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We say that a dataset is rationalizable, when there is a rational demand
 correspondence such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{k}\in x(p^{k},p^{k}x^{k})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a rational demand correspondence.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Rationalizability.
 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{K}$
\end_inset

 is (weakly) rationalizable if there exist a rational 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 such that if 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{k}x^{k}\geq p^{k}y$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{k}\succeq y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We emphasize that we need to assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 are locally non-satiated and that Walras' law holds.
 Else, we do not have empirical content for the rational preference maximization
 theory.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Fact
Any dataset 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{K}$
\end_inset

 can be (weakly) rationalized by a 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Locally non-satiated preferences.
 We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is locally non-satiated when for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in X$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $||y-x||\leq\epsilon$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\succ x$
\end_inset

 (and 
\begin_inset Formula $||\cdot||$
\end_inset

 is some norm in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unless we stated differently, we say that 
\begin_inset Formula $||\cdot||$
\end_inset

 is a norm in the Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $w^{k}=p^{k}x^{k}$
\end_inset

 (not an innocent assumption).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Utility representation.
 We say a utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $u:X\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 represents 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $u(a)\geq u(b)\iff a\succeq b$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sometimes we care, or we want to exploit shape constraints on the utility
 function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Concave utility function.
 A utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is concave whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)-u(y)\geq\xi(x-y)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi\in\nabla u(x)$
\end_inset

, for a fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla u(x)$
\end_inset

 as the super-gradient of a utility function and it can be set-valued, 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi\in\nabla u(x)$
\end_inset

 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi\in\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Supergradient.
 We say that the supergradient of a concave function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 (where it exists), 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla f(x)$
\end_inset

 is the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi\in\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)-u(y)\geq\xi[x-y]$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We notice that when 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is differentiable 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla u(x)=\{\xi\}$
\end_inset

 and this is called the gradient.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We recall that when 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is concave the FOC from the KKT are necessary and sufficient for having
 the existence of a maximum of the UMP.
 Afriat's Theorem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we are going to focus instead on FOC and exploiting concavity for models
 beyond UMP.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
A dataset 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{K}$
\end_inset

 is rationalizable (by means of a concave utility) if and only if there
 exists a concave 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and a vector of positive values 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\lambda^{k}\}_{k=1}^{K}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{k}>0$
\end_inset

 such that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\xi\leq\lambda^{k}p^{k}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\xi\in\nabla u(x^{k}),
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
with equality for interior solutions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using KKT we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $max_{x\geq0}u(x)$
\end_inset

 subject to 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{k}x\leq p^{k}x^{k}$
\end_inset

 will give me the FOC, for now assume 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is differentiable:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nabla u(x^{k})=\lambda^{k}p^{k}+\psi^{k},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{k}>0$
\end_inset

, and:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi_{l}^{k}x_{l}^{k}=0\quad\forall l=1,\cdots,L
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda^{k}[p^{k}x-p^{k}x^{k}]=0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first case:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{l}^{k}>0:\nabla u(x^{k})_{l}=\lambda^{k}p_{l}^{k}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{l}^{k}=0:\lambda^{k}p_{l}^{k}>\nabla u(x^{k})_{l},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
this implies:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda^{k}p^{k}\geq\nabla u(x^{k}),
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with equality for interior solutions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Revealed-Preference First-Order Approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset FormulaMacro
\newcommand{\tr}{^{\prime}}
\end_inset


\begin_inset FormulaMacro
\newcommand{\rand}[1]{\mathbf{#1}}
\end_inset


\begin_inset FormulaMacro
\newcommand{\rands}[1]{\boldsymbol{#1}}
\end_inset


\begin_inset FormulaMacro
\newcommand{\rat}{R}
\end_inset


\begin_inset FormulaMacro
\newcommand{\q}{Q}
\end_inset


\begin_inset FormulaMacro
\newcommand{\ed}{ED}
\end_inset


\begin_inset FormulaMacro
\newcommand{\m}{m}
\end_inset


\begin_inset FormulaMacro
\newcommand{\Real}{\mathbb{R}}
\end_inset


\begin_inset FormulaMacro
\newcommand{\Natural}{\mathbb{N}}
\end_inset


\begin_inset FormulaMacro
\newcommand{\Exp}[1]{\mathbf{\mathbb{E}\left[#1\right]}}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section is heavily based on Aguiar and Kashaev (2020).
 The main objective of this section is to study the models of static utility
 maximization (
\begin_inset Formula $\rat$
\end_inset

) and quasilinear utility maximization (
\begin_inset Formula $\q$
\end_inset

).
 We also investigate the case of dynamic rationality, also called the exponentia
l discounting (
\begin_inset Formula $\ed$
\end_inset

) model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let the consumption space be 
\begin_inset Formula $\Real_{+}^{L}\setminus\{0\}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $L\in\Natural_{+}$
\end_inset

 is the number of commodities.
 Consider a consumer who is endowed with a utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $u:\Real_{+}^{L}\to\Real$
\end_inset

 that is assumed to be concave, locally nonsatiated, and continuous.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We use the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\Natural_{+}$
\end_inset

 to denote the set of strictly positive natural numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1,2,3,\cdots\}$
\end_inset

.
 The expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\Real_{+}^{L}$
\end_inset

 denotes the nonnegative euclidean space of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $L\geq1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Real_{+}^{L}\setminus{0}$
\end_inset

 denotes the set of vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in\Real_{+}^{L}$
\end_inset

 that are distinct from zero (
\begin_inset Formula $v\neq0$
\end_inset

).
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Real_{+,+}^{L}$
\end_inset

 represents the strictly positive euclidean space of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $L\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 The inner product of two vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1},v_{2}\in\Real_{+}^{L}$
\end_inset

 is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}\tr v_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The consumer faces a sequence of decision problems indexed by 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}=\{0,\cdots,T\}$
\end_inset

, with a known and finite 
\begin_inset Formula $T\in\Natural_{+}$
\end_inset

.
 At each decision problem 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

, the consumer faces the price vector 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{t}\in\Real_{++}^{L}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Static 
\begin_inset Formula $\m$
\end_inset

-rationalizability) For any 
\begin_inset Formula $\m\in\{\rat,\q\}$
\end_inset

, a deterministic array 
\begin_inset Formula $(p_{t},c_{t})_{t\in\mathcal{T}}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\m$
\end_inset

-rationalizable (in a static sense) if for some constants 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{t}^{\m}\in\Real$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

, the consumption bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}$
\end_inset

 solves: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
 & \max_{c\in\Real_{+}^{L}}u(c)+z_{t}^{\m},\\
 & \text{s.t. }p_{t}\tr c+z_{t}^{\m}=y_{t},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rational case requires that the constant 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{t}^{\rat}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

.
 The quasilinear utility case requires that 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{t}^{\q}>0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

.
 The interpretation of 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{t}^{\q}$
\end_inset

 is that it is a numeraire or composite outside commodity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next we focus our attention on the dynamic consumer model of exponential
 discounting (
\begin_inset Formula $\ed$
\end_inset

).
 We assume that an individual consumer has preferences over a stream of
 dated consumption bundles 
\begin_inset Formula $(c_{t})_{t\in\mathcal{T}}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}=\{0,\cdots,T\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T\in\Natural_{+}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}\in\Real_{+}^{L}\setminus\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 (The number of goods, 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, is kept the same across the time interval.) At time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, the consumer chooses how much 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 she will consume by maximizing 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{\tau}(c)=u(c_{\tau})+\sum_{j=1}^{T-\tau}d^{j}u(c_{\tau+j}),
\]

\end_inset

subject to the linear budget or flow constraints shown here: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{t}\tr c_{t}-y_{t}+s_{t}-a_{t}=0,\quad t=\tau,\dots,T,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $d\in(0,1]$
\end_inset

 is the discount factor; 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{t}\in\Real_{++}^{L}$
\end_inset

 is the price vector as before; 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}\in\Real_{++}$
\end_inset

 is income received by the individual at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the amount of savings held by the consumer at the end of time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

; and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the volume of assets held at the start of time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 The consumer invests all her savings.
 Moreover, the assets evolve according to the following law of motion: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{t}=(1+r_{t})s_{t-1},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t+1}>-1$
\end_inset

 is the interest rate that is accessible for the consumer.
 The holdings of assets in the last period (
\begin_inset Formula $t=T$
\end_inset

) are set to be zero.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The intertemporal value function, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{t}:\Real_{+}^{L\times(T-t+1)}\to\Real_{++}$
\end_inset

, represents the consumer preferences at a given time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 The components of this representation are the parameters of the model.
 First, 
\begin_inset Formula $d\in(0,1]$
\end_inset

 is a scalar number that measures the degree of discount that the consumer
 gives to the future.
 Second, 
\begin_inset Formula $u:\Real_{+}^{L}\to\Real_{++}$
\end_inset

 is an instantaneous utility function that is assumed to be concave, locally
 nonsatiated, and continuous.
 The exponential discounting consumer is time-consistent, that is, she will
 solve the same problem at any point of the time window.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(
\begin_inset Formula $\ed$
\end_inset

-rationalizability) A deterministic array 
\begin_inset Formula $(p_{t},r_{t},c_{t})_{t\in\mathcal{T}}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\ed$
\end_inset

-rationalizable if there exist 
\begin_inset Formula $(y_{t})_{t\in\mathcal{T}}\in\Real_{++}^{|\mathcal{T}|}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{t})_{t\in\mathcal{T}}$
\end_inset

 such that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\in\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

, the consumption stream 
\begin_inset Formula $(c_{j})_{j=\tau}^{T}$
\end_inset

 solves: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\max_{z\in\Real_{+}^{L\times(T-\tau+1)}}u(z_{\tau})+\sum_{j=1}^{T-\tau}d^{j}u(z_{\tau+j}),
\]

\end_inset

subject to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
 & p_{\tau}\tr z_{\tau}+\sum_{j=1}^{T-\tau}\frac{p_{\tau+j}\tr z_{\tau+j}}{\prod_{i=1}^{j}[1+r_{\tau+i}]}=\sum_{j=1}^{T-\tau}\frac{y_{\tau+j}}{\prod_{i=1}^{j}[1+r_{\tau+i}]}+a_{\tau},\\
 & a_{j+1}=(1+r_{j+1})(y_{j}+a_{j}-p_{j}\tr c_{j}),\quad j=\tau,\dots,T,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{T}=0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we establish that any consumer model 
\begin_inset Formula $\m\in\{\rat,\q,\ed\}$
\end_inset

 can be completely characterized in terms of its first-order conditions
 with respect to a (i) concave, locally nonsatiated, and continuous utility
 function 
\begin_inset Formula $u:\Real_{+}^{L}\to\Real$
\end_inset

, (ii) the effective (or transformed) prices 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{t}^{\m}\in\Real_{++}^{L}$
\end_inset

, and (iii) restrictions on some constants 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{t}^{\m}\in\Real_{++}$
\end_inset

, interpreted as the marginal utility of income, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

.
 We call this the first-order conditions approach.
 Observe that the utility function is model-independent, but the effective
 prices and marginal utility of income are not.
 We define the effective prices in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "table:Lambdarhodef"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Tabular
<lyxtabular version="3" rows="3" columns="6">
<features booktabs="true" islongtable="true" longtabularalignment="center">
<column alignment="center" valignment="top">
