\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Sparse-Max Cobb-Douglas Consumer Comparative Statics Analysis
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Choice over Time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a consumer that faces a choice problem over consumption streams
 over time.
 Say that time is a finite set
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}=\{0,1,2,\cdots,T$
\end_inset

}.
 Consumption streams are arrays of consumption vectors that are dated by
 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c=\{c_{t}\}_{t=0}^{T}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}\in\mathbb{R}_{++}^{L}$
\end_inset

.
 Our primitive now is 
\begin_inset Formula $Z^{\mathcal{T}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=\mathbb{R}_{++}^{L}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are going to study a class of rational preferences 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $Z^{T}$
\end_inset

 that are called the exponential discounting preferences:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c\succ c'\iff\sum_{t=0}^{T}\delta^{t}u(c_{t})>\sum_{t=0}^{T}\delta^{t}u(c_{t}').
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first step is to characterize these class of preferences, we propose
 the following behavioral axioms.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
(Sensitivity of the first period) There exist 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in Z$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in Z^{T}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,x_{1},\cdots,x_{T})\succ(b,x_{1},\cdots,x_{T})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that you care about what you get at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
(Initial separability) For all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c,d\in Z$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in Z^{\mathcal{T}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b,x_{2},\cdots,x_{T})\succ(c,d,x_{2},\cdots,x_{T})$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b,y_{2},\cdots,y_{T})\succ(c,d,y_{2},\cdots,y_{T})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that the marginal rate of substitution between consumption in
 time period 0 and time period 1 does not depend on consumption on the rest
 of time periods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
(Stationary) 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,x_{0},\cdots,x_{T-1})\succ(a,y_{0},\cdots,y_{T-1})$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{0},\cdots,x_{T-1},a)\succ(y_{0},\cdots,y_{T-1},a)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the key axiom.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
(Continuity) 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a standard technical condition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
A preference 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $Z^{\mathcal{T}}$
\end_inset

 satisfies Axioms initial sensitivity, initial separability, stationarity
 (continuity), if and only if there exists a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta>0$
\end_inset

, and a function 
\begin_inset Formula $u:Z\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 continuous such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

 is represented as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U(c)=\sum_{t=0}^{T}\delta^{t}u(c_{t}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

(Sketch)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Use initial separability to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

 are separable from the rest, use stationarity to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{t,t+1\}$
\end_inset

 are separable.
 Use initial sensibility to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1\}$
\end_inset

 are separable.
 This gives us a separable representation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{U}(c)=\sum_{t=0}^{T}v_{t}(c_{t})$
\end_inset

.
 Use stationarity to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t+1}=\delta v_{t}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta>0$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $u=v_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 I am getting 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t}=\delta^{t}u$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Discounting and Time Consistency
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The exponential discounting model has a very interesting property, it represents
 the preference of a consumer that is time consistent.
 In short, a time consistent consumer chooses the same consumption stream
 whether she is given the decision task at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 and then forced to get the chosen consumption stream until 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, and when she can choose the consumption level at each period of time recursive
ly or sequentially.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a decision maker deciding at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

, and she gets to commit to consumption in each of the three periods.
 In other words, the DM solves the problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
max_{c_{0},c_{1},c_{2}}u(c_{0})+\delta u(c_{1})+\delta^{2}u(c_{2})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
subject to 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{0}+c_{1}+c_{2}=3y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can solve this problem by setting up the Lagrangian:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}=u(c_{0})+\delta u(c_{1})+\delta^{2}u(c_{2})-\lambda(c_{0}+c_{1}+c_{2}-3y)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which gives the following FOC:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u'(c_{0})=\lambda
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta u'(c_{1})=\lambda
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta^{2}u'(c_{2})=\lambda.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume that preferences have the following shape:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(c)=\frac{c^{1-\sigma}}{1-\sigma}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\neq1$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $u'(c)=c^{-\sigma}$
\end_inset

, so we get:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{0}^{-\sigma}=\delta c_{1}^{-\sigma}=\delta^{2}c_{2}^{-\sigma}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that this can be written as the Euler Equation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
MRS=\frac{c_{t}^{-\sigma}}{c_{t+1}^{-\sigma}}=\delta.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Replacing the FOC in the budget constraint:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{0}+\delta^{1/\sigma}c_{0}+(\delta^{2})^{1/\sigma}c_{0}=3y
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{0}=\frac{3y}{1+\delta^{1/\sigma}+(\delta^{2})^{1/\sigma}},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{1}=(\delta)^{1/\sigma}c_{0}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{2}=(\delta^{2})^{1/\sigma}c_{0}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Say now that the consumer gets to re-evaluate her choices at each period
 of time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0,1,2$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, this is called, the cake-eating problem.
 You get a cake 
\begin_inset Formula $3y$
\end_inset

 and you decide each day how much to eat today and how much to save.
 At the last period of time the consumer has nothing to decide and experiences
 utility:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(c_{2}),
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
at time 1, she faces a trade-off between 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(c_{1})+\delta u(c_{2})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and at time 0, she faces a trade-off between 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1,2\}$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(c_{0})+\delta u(c_{1})+\delta^{2}u(c_{2}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can solve the problem backwards, in the last period, the consumer will
 obviously just eat whatever it is they have left.
 Thus if they arrive at time 2 with remaining cake 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{2}=3y-c_{1}-c_{0}$
\end_inset

, their consumption will be:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{2}=w_{2}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At time 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, the consumer faces the problem of consuming the remaining cake 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{1}=3y-c_{0}$
\end_inset

, with the utility:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(c_{1})+\delta u(c_{2}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solving this problem gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{2}=\delta^{1/\sigma}c_{1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At time 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, the consumer faces the problem of consuming the cake 
\begin_inset Formula $3y$
\end_inset

 under the utility:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(c_{0})+\delta u(c_{2})+\delta u(c_{3})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the same problem as before and we already know that,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{1}=\delta^{1/\sigma}c_{0}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{0}$
\end_inset

 from this last stage is the same as before: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{0}=\frac{3y}{1+\delta^{1/\sigma}+(\delta^{2})^{1/\sigma}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let's go to time 1, in this case,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w_{1}=3y-c_{0},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{1}+\delta^{1/\sigma}c_{1}=3y-c_{0}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{1}(1+\delta^{1/\sigma})(1+\delta^{1/\sigma}+(\delta^{2})^{1/\sigma})=3y(1+\delta^{1/\sigma}+(\delta^{2})^{1/\sigma})-3y
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{1}(1+\delta^{1/\sigma})(1+\delta^{1/\sigma}+(\delta^{2})^{1/\sigma})=3y\delta^{1/\sigma}(1+(\delta)^{1/\sigma})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{1}=\delta^{1/\sigma}c_{0}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By the FOC of the problem at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{2}=\delta^{1/\sigma}c_{1}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The consumer is time consistent as she chooses exactly the same thing in
 either of the two following situations: if she gets to commit at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 or if she gets to choose at each 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0,1,2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Hyperbolic Discounting Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we consider a consumer that is time inconsistent.
 This consumer is present-biased.
 The preference relation is represented by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c\succ c'\iff u(c_{0})+\beta\delta\sum_{t=1}^{T}\delta^{t-1}u(c_{t})>u(c_{0}')+\beta\delta\sum_{t=1}^{T}\delta^{t-1}u(c_{t}'),
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 is the long-run discount factor and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\in(0,1]$
\end_inset

 is the short-run discount factor that captures the strength of the present
 bias.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Quasi-Hyperbolic consumer fails stationarity.
 Instead she satisfies:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
(Quasistationary) 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b,x_{0},\cdots,x_{T-2})\succ(a,b,y_{0},\cdots,y_{T-2})$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,x_{0},\cdots,x_{T-2},b)\succ(a,y_{0},\cdots,y_{T-1},b)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can verify that Quasistationarity is a necessary condition (an implication).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(a)+\beta\delta u(b)+\beta\delta\sum_{t=2}^{T}\delta^{t-1}u(x_{t-2})>,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(a)+\beta\delta u(b)+\beta\delta\sum_{t=2}^{T}\delta^{t-1}u(y_{t-2}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta\delta[u(b)+\sum_{t=2}^{T}\delta^{t-1}u(x_{t-2})]>
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta\delta[u(b)+\sum_{t=2}^{T}\delta^{t-1}u(y_{t-2})]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is equivalent to:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(b)+\sum_{t=2}^{T}\delta^{t-1}u(x_{t-2})>
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(b)+\sum_{t=2}^{T}\delta^{t-1}u(y_{t-2}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But this is exactly the exponential discounting model that we know satisfies
 stationarity.
 This implies that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x_{0})+\sum_{t=3}^{T}\delta^{t-1}u(x_{t-2})+\delta^{T}u(b)>
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(y_{0})+\sum_{t=3}^{T}\delta^{t-1}u(y_{t-2})+\delta^{T}u(b).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Plugging back this implies:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(a)+\beta\delta[u(x_{0})+\sum_{t=3}^{T}\delta^{t-1}u(x_{t-2})+\delta^{T}u(b)]>
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(a)+\beta\delta[u(y_{0})+\sum_{t=3}^{T}\delta^{t-1}u(y_{t-2})+\delta^{T}u(b)].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Present Bias in the Cake Eating Problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a decision maker deciding at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

, and she gets to commit to consumption in each of the three periods.
 In other words, the DM solves the problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
max_{c_{0},c_{1},c_{2}}u(c_{0})+\beta\delta u(c_{1})+\beta\delta^{2}u(c_{2})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
subject to 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{0}+c_{1}+c_{2}=3y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can solve this problem by setting up the Lagrangian:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}=u(c_{0})+\delta u(c_{1})+\delta^{2}u(c_{2})-\lambda(c_{0}+c_{1}+c_{2}-3y)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which gives the following FOC:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u'(c_{0})=\lambda
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta\delta u'(c_{1})=\lambda
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta\delta^{2}u'(c_{2})=\lambda.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume that preferences have the following shape:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(c)=\frac{c^{1-\sigma}}{1-\sigma}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\neq1$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $u'(c)=c^{-\sigma}$
\end_inset

, so we get:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{0}^{-\sigma}=\beta\delta c_{1}^{-\sigma}=\beta\delta^{2}c_{2}^{-\sigma}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that this can be written as the Euler Equation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
MRS_{0,1}=\frac{c_{0}^{-\sigma}}{c_{1}^{-\sigma}}=\beta\delta.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
MRS_{1,2}=\frac{c_{1}^{-\sigma}}{c_{2}^{-\sigma}}=\delta.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Replacing the FOC in the budget constraint:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{0}+(\beta\delta)^{1/\sigma}c_{0}+(\beta\delta^{2})^{1/\sigma}c_{0}=3y
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{0}=\frac{3y}{1+(\beta\delta)^{1/\sigma}+(\beta\delta^{2})^{1/\sigma}},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{1}=(\beta\delta)^{1/\sigma}c_{0}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{2}=(\beta\delta^{2})^{1/\sigma}c_{0}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Say now that the consumer gets to re-evaluate her choices at each period
 of time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0,1,2$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the last period of time the consumer gets:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(c_{2}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From period 1:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(c_{1})+\beta\delta u(c_{2})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and from period 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(c_{0})+\beta\delta u(c_{1})+\beta\delta^{2}u(c_{2}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solving period 1:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u'(c_{1})=\beta\delta u'(c_{2}),
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
given the budget constrain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{1}+(\beta\delta)^{1/\sigma}c_{1}=3y-c_{0}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{1}(1+(\beta\delta)^{1/\sigma})[1+(\beta\delta)^{1/\sigma}+(\beta\delta^{2})^{1/\sigma}]=3y[(\beta\delta)^{1/\sigma}+(\beta\delta^{2})^{1/\sigma}]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{1}(1+(\beta\delta)^{1/\sigma})[1+(\beta\delta)^{1/\sigma}+(\beta\delta^{2})^{1/\sigma}]=(\beta\delta)^{1/\sigma}3y[1+(\delta)^{1/\sigma}]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{1}=(\beta\delta)^{1/\sigma}\frac{3y}{[1+(\beta\delta)^{1/\sigma}+(\beta\delta^{2})^{1/\sigma}]}\frac{[1+(\delta)^{1/\sigma}]}{(1+(\beta\delta)^{1/\sigma})}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{1}=(\beta\delta)^{1/\sigma}c_{0}\frac{[1+(\delta)^{1/\sigma}]}{(1+(\beta\delta)^{1/\sigma})}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This solution is different from the 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 solution (commitment solution):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{1}=(\beta\delta)^{1/\sigma}c_{0},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
when 
\begin_inset Formula $0<\beta<1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In fact 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}^{hyperbolic}>c_{1}^{commit}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Testing Exponential Discounting vs.
 Hyperbolic Discounting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Results from a Revealed Preference Experiment by Andreoni and Spengler.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In each decision, subjects choose either an amount 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}$
\end_inset

, available at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, or an amount 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t+k}>c_{t}$
\end_inset

 available after a delay of 
\begin_inset Formula $k>0$
\end_inset

 periods.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(1+r)$
\end_inset

 be the experimental gross interest rate and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 be the experimental budget.
 The procedure ask the subjects to choose an alternative from the discrete
 budget set 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(1+r)c_{t}+c_{t+k}=m.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To operationalize this, the subjects are provided 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

tokens
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The tokens can be allocated to either a sooner time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, or a later time 
\begin_inset Formula $t+k$
\end_inset

 at different token exchange rates.
 The relative rate at which the tokens translate into payments determine
 the gross interest rate 
\begin_inset Formula $(1+r)$
\end_inset

.
 Subjects choose how many tokens to allocate to sooner and later periods.
 This is called the Convex Time Budget (CTB) approach.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Design Features.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The experiment was conducted at UCSD in 2009.
 Subjects faced 45 convex budget set decisions.
 These 45 budgets involved nine combinations of starting times 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, and delay lengths 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, with annual interest rates that varied from zero to over 1000
\begin_inset Formula $\%$
\end_inset

 per year.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Payments were scheduled to arrive at the same day of the week, to avoid
 differential weekday effects.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In each CTB problem subjects were given a budget of 
\begin_inset Formula $100$
\end_inset

 tokens.
 Tokens today had a value of 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{t}$
\end_inset

 and then had a value of 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{t+k}.$
\end_inset

 In most cases, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{t+k}$
\end_inset

 was about 
\begin_inset Formula $\$0.20$
\end_inset

 per token and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{t}$
\end_inset

 varied from 
\begin_inset Formula $\$0.2$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\$.10$
\end_inset

 per token.
 The rate 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{t+k}/a_{t}=1+r$
\end_inset

.
 Payments were done by the University mail services in a delayed form but
 there was no uncertainty about getting the payments.
 Only students living in campus could participate.
 The participants received a $10 participation fee but no payment was done
 in the lab.
 The $10 payment was done 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sooner
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

later
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 irrespective of the choices.
 This eliminates any inconvenience gained by concentrating payments in one
 period, two checks were sent regardless.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Wrap figure
lines 0
placement o
overhang 0col%
width "50col%"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename C:/Users/pegasuspc/Documents/WesternAP/FirstYear/UndergraduateAdvancedMicro/notes/figures/exponential_disc_hyperbolic_disc_pass_rates.png
	scale 70

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
AS, is Andreoni-Spengler experiment.
 CMW is another experiment based on an online survey with a finance focus,
 we are not going to focus on that.
 EDU stands for Exponential Discounting Utility.
 QHD stands for quasi-hyperbolic discounting.
 TSU is another model we have not studied and we are going to ignore.
 The following relation holds 
\begin_inset Formula $EDU\subset QHD\subset TSU$
\end_inset

, the numerical cells captures the pass rate of each model free of the smaller
 subset.
 For instance 
\begin_inset Formula $0.299$
\end_inset

 is the pass rate of the Quasi Hyperbolic model on top of the exponential
 discounting pass rate that is a subcase of it.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Wrap figure
lines 0
placement o
overhang 0col%
width "50col%"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../../FirstYear/UndergraduateAdvancedMicro/notes/figures/AndreoniSpenglerJavainterface.png
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Example of the dialog screen for the Andreoni-Spengler experiment.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Naive vs.
 Sophisticated Hyperbolic Consumer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Solve the Naive quasi-hyperbolic cake-eating consumer problem.
 The size of the cake is 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

, the discount factor is 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

.
 There is a price in each period for eating the cake and time runs from
 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1,2,3$
\end_inset

.
 We use 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}$
\end_inset

 for the period of time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The optimization problem for a consumer that can pre-commit (superscript
 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

) is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $max_{\{x_{i}^{p}\}_{i=1,2,3.}}u(x_{1}^{p})+\beta\delta u(x_{2}^{p})+\beta\delta^{2}u(x_{3}^{p})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
subject to the budget constraint
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{3}p_{i}x_{i}^{p}=w$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first order conditions are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $u'(x_{1}^{p})=\lambda p_{1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\delta u'(x_{2}^{p})=\lambda p_{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\delta^{2}u'(x_{3}^{p})=\lambda p_{3}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With CRRA utility with relative risk aversion 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $u'(x_{i}^{p})=[x_{i}^{p}]^{-\sigma}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{p}=[\beta\delta\frac{p_{1}}{p_{2}}]^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}x_{1}^{p}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}^{p}=[\beta\delta^{2}\frac{p_{1}}{p_{3}}]^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}x_{1}^{p}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then, imposing the budget constraint:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}x_{1}^{p}+p_{2}[\beta\delta\frac{p_{1}}{p_{2}}]^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}x_{1}^{p}+p_{3}[\beta\delta^{2}\frac{p_{1}}{p_{3}}]{}^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}x_{1}^{p}=w$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which gives the demand system:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{p}=[p_{1}+p_{2}[\beta\delta\frac{p_{1}}{p_{2}}]^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}+p_{3}[\beta\delta^{2}\frac{p_{1}}{p_{3}}]{}^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}]^{-1}w$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{p}=[\beta\delta\frac{p_{1}}{p_{2}}]^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}x_{1}^{p}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}^{p}=[\beta\delta^{2}\frac{p_{1}}{p_{3}}]^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}x_{1}^{p}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The naive quasi-hyperbolic discounter will have the following demand system:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the first period, the consumer assumes he will stick to his commitment
 in the second period and consumes the same amount as in the pre-commitment
 case:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{h}=[p_{1}+p_{2}[\beta\delta\frac{p_{1}}{p_{2}}]^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}+p_{3}[\beta\delta^{2}\frac{p_{1}}{p_{3}}]{}^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}]^{-1}w$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, when period two arrives, he re-optimizes taking as given the remaining
 wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $w-p_{1}x_{1}^{h}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{h}=\frac{w-p_{1}x_{1}^{h}}{p_{2}+p_{3}[\beta\delta\frac{p_{2}}{p_{3}}]^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}^{h}=[\beta\delta\frac{p_{2}}{p_{3}}]^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}x_{2}^{h}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We call it naive, because he thinks that after tomorrow he is going to be
 time consistent even when this is not true.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Solve the Sophisticated Quasi-hyperbolic cake-eating problem.
 The sophisticated Quasi-hyperbolic problem, is different from what we saw
 in class in the following aspect, the sophisticated consumers knows that
 she is not going to be able to control herself, and thus she foresees this
 at time 1 and underconsumes in an optimal way in the first period to be
 closer in terms of utility to the commitment case and to the time consistency.
 (Think of Ulyses' solution to avoid falling for the Mermaids singing.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We build this example as a followup to the naive quasi-hyperbolic consumer.
 In this case, the consumer knows that in 
\begin_inset Formula $t=2$
\end_inset

 she will not be able to keep her commitment and therefore will adjust her
 consumption at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1$
\end_inset

.
 Then the consumer maximizes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
max_{x_{1}^{sh}}u(x_{1}^{sh})+\beta\delta u(x_{2}^{h})+\beta\delta^{2}u(x_{3}^{h})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{h},x_{3}^{h}$
\end_inset

 are known to her in 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1$
\end_inset

 and depend on period 1 consumption.
 However, she can control only how much she consumes in the first period.
 Taking first order conditions and keeping the assumption of the naive quasi-hyp
erbolic case, the first order conditions are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u'(x_{1}^{sh})+\beta\delta u'(x_{2}^{h})\frac{\partial x_{2}^{h}}{\partial x_{1}^{sh}}+\beta\delta^{2}u'(x_{3}^{h})\frac{\partial x_{3}^{h}}{\partial x_{1}^{sh}}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under the parametric assumptions made in the previous example, the new demand
 system of the sophisticated hyperbolic discounter is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $u'(x_{i}^{p})=[x_{i}^{p}]^{-\sigma}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[x_{1}^{sh}]^{-\sigma}+\beta\delta[x_{2}^{h}]^{-\sigma}\frac{\partial x_{2}^{h}}{\partial x_{1}^{sh}}+\beta\delta^{2}[x_{3}^{h}]^{-\sigma}\frac{\partial x_{3}^{h}}{\partial x_{1}^{sh}}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{h}=\frac{w-p_{1}x_{1}^{h}}{p_{2}+p_{3}[\beta\delta\frac{p_{2}}{p_{3}}]^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}^{h}=[\beta\delta\frac{p_{2}}{p_{3}}]^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}x_{2}^{h}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial x_{2}^{h}}{\partial x_{1}^{sh}}=\frac{p_{1}}{p_{2}+p_{3}[\frac{p_{2\beta\delta}}{p_{3}}]^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial x_{3}^{h}}{\partial x_{1}^{sh}}=-\frac{p_{1}[\frac{p_{2}\beta\delta}{p_{3}}]^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}}{p_{2}+p_{3}[\frac{p_{2\beta\delta}}{p_{3}}]^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then the first period consumption under the sophisticated hyperbolic discounting
 is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{1}^{sh}=\left[\left[\frac{p_{1}\beta\delta+p_{1}\beta\delta^{2}[\beta\delta\frac{p_{2}}{p_{3}}]^{\frac{1-\sigma}{\sigma}}}{\left[p_{2}+p_{3}[\beta\delta\frac{p_{2}}{p_{3}}]^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}\right]^{1-\sigma}}\right]^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}+p_{1}\right]^{-1}w.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Compare the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{sh}$
\end_inset

 to the naive solution 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{h}=[p_{1}+p_{2}[\beta\delta\frac{p_{1}}{p_{2}}]^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}+p_{3}[\beta\delta^{2}\frac{p_{1}}{p_{3}}]{}^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}]^{-1}w$
\end_inset

, these two are different.
 The sophisticated consumer changes the consumption path in the first period
 to try to minimize losses to her own welfare due to her time inconsistency.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Slutsky Matrix Analysis: Demand Function Generated by Unobserved Sequential
 Choice: Naive Quasi-Hyperbolic Discounting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this example, we study the case of a demand function that is generated
 by a sequential decision-making procedure, that is latent or hidden for
 the modeller.
 In particular, the modeller observes a (static) demand function when the
 actual decision-making takes place in a three-period environment.
 We assume that the consumer cannot make her consumption decision for all
 goods at once.
 Instead, the consumer receives an amount of wealth at the initial time
 period.
 Then she must first decide how much to buy from good 1, then how much to
 purchase from good 2, and the final day, she spends the remaining money
 in the third good.
 Our aim is to measure the violations of property 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{R}$
\end_inset

 by a naive and sophisticated quasi-hyperbolic discounters.
 The optimization problem for a consumer that can pre-commit is: 
\begin_inset Formula $max_{\{x_{i}^{p}\}_{i=1,2,3.}}u(x_{1}^{p})+\beta\theta u(x_{2}^{p})+\beta\theta^{2}u(x_{3}^{p})$
\end_inset

 subject to the budget constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{3}p_{i}x_{i}^{p}=w$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The solution of this problem gives the demand system: (i) 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{p}=[p_{1}+p_{2}[\beta\theta\frac{p_{1}}{p_{2}}]^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}+p_{3}[\beta\theta^{2}\frac{p_{1}}{p_{3}}]{}^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}]^{-1}w$
\end_inset

.
 (ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{p}=[\beta\theta\frac{p_{1}}{p_{2}}]^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}x_{1}^{p}$
\end_inset

 (iii) 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}^{p}=[\beta\theta^{2}\frac{p_{1}}{p_{3}}]^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}x_{1}^{p}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This is called the exponential discounting solution and it produces a demand
 system that is consistent with rationality.
 In contrast, the naive quasi-hyperbolic discounter will have the following
 demand system: In the first period, the consumer assumes she will stick
 to her commitment in the second period, and consumes the same amount as
 in the pre-commitment case (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{h}=x_{1}^{p}$
\end_inset

).
 However, when period 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 arrives, she re-optimizes taking as given the remaining wealth and chooses:
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{h}=\frac{w-p_{1}x_{1}^{h}}{p_{2}+p_{3}[\beta\theta\frac{p_{2}}{p_{3}}]^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}^{h}=[\beta\theta\frac{p_{2}}{p_{3}}]^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}x_{2}^{h}.$
\end_inset

 The analytical result for the matrix nearness norm has a nice expression
 (for simplicity we fix 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{j}=1,w=1$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $j=\{1,2,3\}$
\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
||E^{h}(p,w)||_{\mathbb{M}}^{2}=\frac{3}{2}\frac{(\sigma-1)^{2}\left(\left(\beta\theta\right)^{\frac{2}{\sigma}}-\left(\beta\theta^{2}\right)^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}\right)^{2}}{\sigma^{2}\left(\left(\beta\theta\right)^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}+1\right)^{2}\left(\left(\beta\theta\right)^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}+\left(\beta\theta^{2}\right)^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}+1\right)^{4}},
\]

\end_inset

which readily gives us that: 
\begin_inset Formula $||E^{h}(p,w)||_{\mathbb{M}}^{2}=0$
\end_inset

 when either (i) 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=1$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=0$
\end_inset

 (i.e., the demand is rational); (ii) or 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1$
\end_inset

, and finally (iii) when 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\rightarrow0,\theta\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, in the limit cases the hyperbolic demand system is rational.
 Take for instance case (iii), because the agent consumes everything in
 the first period and gives no weight to the other time periods then it
 is trivially rational, with 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{r}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{h}\rightarrow\frac{w}{p1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{h},x_{3}^{h}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

.
 In case (i), the logarithmic utility case, the hyperbolic discounter manages
 to keep her commitment and therefore her consumption is time consistent
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $||E^{h}(p,w)||_{\mathbb{M}}^{2}=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
For any two consumers consistent with the naive quasi-hyperbolic behavior,
 who have the same CRRA utility, but different present-bias parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{2}>\beta_{1}$
\end_inset

, one can conclude that consumer 1 is more boundedly rational than consumer
 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 (when 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma>1$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\in(0,1]$
\end_inset

).
 This means that the higher the present bias, the higher the Slutsky matrix
 norm.
 Another observation that we can draw from this example is that only the
 ICPP anomaly appears (i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $||E||^{2}=||E^{\sigma}||^{2}$
\end_inset

).
 This seems to make sense, as increases in purchasing power may be offset
 by the sequential nature of the consumer choice and the temporal inconsistencie
s it introduces.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Slutsky Matrix Analysis: Demand Function Generated by Unobserved Sequential
 Choice: Sophisticated Quasi-Hyperbolic Discounting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One would expect that the sophisticated quasi-hyperbolic discounter is less
 boundedly rational than the naive case.
 However, the Slutsky matrix norm helps to appreciate some of the subtleties
 and assess which conditions of rationality are fulfilled by this type of
 consumer.
 In fact, we establish that the sophisticated quasi-hyperbolic discounter
 can generate demand functions that are more boundedly rational in the sense
 of the Slutsky matrix norm than the naive case.
 In other words, actions taken by the sophisticated consumer, understanding
 her time inconsistency, may take her further away from the rationality
 paradigm in terms of small demand reactions to price changes.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In fact, when trying to predict the local behavior (demand changes due to
 small price changes), a modeller may make bigger errors with a sophisticated
 hyperbolic consumer than with a naive one, when imposing rationality.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In the sophisticated case, the consumer knows that in 
\begin_inset Formula $t=2$
\end_inset

 she will not be able to keep her commitment and therefore will adjust her
 consumption at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1$
\end_inset

.
 Then the consumer maximizes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
max_{x_{1}^{sh}}u(x_{1}^{sh})+\beta\theta u(x_{2}^{h})+\beta\theta^{2}u(x_{3}^{h}),
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{h},x_{3}^{h}$
\end_inset

 (conditional on 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{h}$
\end_inset

) are known to her in 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1$
\end_inset

.
 However, she can control only how much she consumes in the first period.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Then, the first period consumption under sophisticated hyperbolic discounting
 is: 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{sh}=\left[\left[p_{1}\beta\theta+p_{1}\beta\theta^{2}[\beta\theta\frac{p_{2}}{p_{3}}]^{\frac{1-\sigma}{\sigma}}/\left[p_{2}+p_{3}[\beta\theta\frac{p_{2}}{p_{3}}]^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}\right]\right]^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}+p_{1}\right]^{-1}w$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Slutsky matrix norm for this consumer is given by the quantity (for
 simplicity we fix 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{j}=1,w=1$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $j=\{1,2,3\}$
\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
||E^{sh}(p,w)||_{\mathbb{M}}^{2}=
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{3}{2}\frac{(\beta-1)^{2}(\sigma-1)^{2}(\beta\theta)^{2/\sigma}\left(\theta\left((\beta\theta)^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}+1\right)^{\sigma-1}\left((\beta\theta)^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}+\beta\right)\right)^{2/\sigma}}{\sigma^{4}\left((\beta\theta)^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}+1\right)^{2}\left((\beta\theta)^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}+\beta\right)^{2}\left(\left(\theta\left((\beta\theta)^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}+1\right)^{\sigma-1}\left((\beta\theta)^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}+\beta\right)\right)^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}+1\right)^{4}}.
\]

\end_inset

This implies that: (i) when 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=0$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

; (ii) when 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=0$
\end_inset

; and (iii) when 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=0$
\end_inset

.
 Also, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $||E||^{2}=||E^{\sigma}||^{2}$
\end_inset

, which means that only the ICCP anomaly appears in this case.
 Now, we compare this quantity with the case of the naive hyperbolic discounter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider the ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $r=\frac{||E^{sh}(p,w)||_{\mathbb{M}}^{2}}{||E^{nh}(p,w)||_{\mathbb{M}}^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $r<1$
\end_inset

, the sophisticated hyperbolic consumer has a lower Slutsky matrix norm
 for any parameter configuration.
 The ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 depends crucially on the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=1$
\end_inset

, both 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{sh},E^{h}$
\end_inset

 are equal to zero: this is a knife-edge case, in which the marginal rates
 of substitution yield optimal consumption equal to the commitment baseline.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma<1$
\end_inset

, the sophisticated hyperbolic discounter has a uniformly lower 
\begin_inset Formula $||E||_{\mathbb{M}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $r<1$
\end_inset

.
 However, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma>1$
\end_inset

 , the naive hyperbolic discounter has a uniformly lower 
\begin_inset Formula $||E||_{\mathbb{M}}^{2}$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $r>1$
\end_inset

.
 Although this may seem counterintuitive, it tells us that the closest rational
 consumer (which need not be the commitment baseline) is closer to the naive
 than to the sophisticated consumer.
 To see this, note that the rational behavior fails due to two possible
 sources: (i) The lack of self-control in the consumption of period 2 (overspend
ing); and (ii) in the case of the sophisticated type, an additional effect
 due to the strategic change in period 1 consumption (overspending or underspend
ing).
 Hence, we find a higher failure for the sophisticated case than in the
 naive case for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma>1$
\end_inset

, because for an increase in prices, for the naive case, the change in period
 1 consumption equals that in the rational case; and only the second and
 third period demand changes are different.
 In contrast, for the sophisticated case, all three good demand changes
 differ from the rational benchmark.
 In particular, the divergence is due to a higher residual wealth at the
 end of period 1, leading to a higher overspending in period 2, for the
 sophisticated case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Consideration Sets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a finite set of choices and 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{X}\setminus\emptyset$
\end_inset

 is the set of menus.
 We consider a case where the consumer has an attention filter.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma:2^{X}\setminus\emptyset\mapsto2^{X}\setminus\emptyset$
\end_inset

 with the following property 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(S\backslash\{x\})\equiv\Gamma(S)$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin\Gamma(S)$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(S)\subseteq S$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The consumer maximizes a utility function subject to the attention filter:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c(S)=argmax_{x\in\Gamma(S)}u(x).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 is free or has no restrictions.
 Then any choice data can be generated by maximizing a utility function
 over the attention filter.
 If we observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $c(S)=\{x\}$
\end_inset

, we can always let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(S)=\{x\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Limited Attention Revealed Preferences
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula $xPy$
\end_inset

 if there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $c(T)=x\neq c(T\setminus y)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $xP_{R}z$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $xPy$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $yPz$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Is this all the information one can recover.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is generated by utility maximization with an attention filter.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is preferred to 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 if and only 
\begin_inset Formula $xP_{R}y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also can recover attention.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is generated by utility maximization with an attention filter.
 Then,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(i) 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is revealed to not attract attention at 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $xP_{R}c(S)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is revealed to attract attention at 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 if and only if there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 (possibly the same as 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

) such that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(a) 
\begin_inset Formula $c(T)\neq c(T\backslash x)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(b) 
\begin_inset Formula $yP_{R}c(S)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in S\backslash T$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $zP_{R}c(T)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in T\backslash S$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We characterize the model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
The following are equivalent.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(i) 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is generated by utility maximization with an attention filter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{R}$
\end_inset

 is acyclic.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sketch.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 (i) 
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

 (ii) (Acyclicity) if 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{1}P_{R}a^{2}\cdots P_{R}a^{n}$
\end_inset

 it implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lnot a^{n}P_{R}a^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $a^{1}P_{R}a^{2}\cdots P_{R}a^{n}$
\end_inset

, if the data were generated for, if 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{1}P_{R}a^{2}$
\end_inset

 then we can conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{1}=c^{u,\Gamma}(A_{1})$
\end_inset

, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $u(a^{1})>u(a^{2})$
\end_inset

.
 This implies if 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{1}P_{R}a^{2}\cdots P_{R}a^{n}$
\end_inset

 this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $u(a^{1})>u(a^{2})\cdots>u(a^{n})$
\end_inset

, if we violate Acyclicity then we have a contradition because 
\begin_inset Formula $u(a^{n})>u(a^{1})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 (ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

 (i) We use the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{R}$
\end_inset

 (the transitive closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

) and we let 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 represents 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{R}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $u(a)>u(b)\iff aP_{R}b$
\end_inset

).
 (ii) We use the attention revelation to build 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

.
 We show that the candiates 
\begin_inset Formula $u,\Gamma$
\end_inset

 generate the data.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are going an example about the attraction effect.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
attraction effect
\series default
 is the observation that if we add an alternative to a menu, then some existing
 item becomes more attractive to the consumer and is picked by her.
 This introduced object is usually called the decoy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In formal terms, 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\{a,b,b^{-}\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{-}\in X$
\end_inset

 be the decoy, so we are going to study its impact in the choice of the
 object of interest 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in X$
\end_inset

.
 The observation is the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b\in c(A\cup\{b^{-}\})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b\notin c(A),b\in A.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It must be that 
\begin_inset Formula $b\notin\Gamma(A)$
\end_inset

 for it to be ignored in menu 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, and then suddenly picked at menu 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cup\{b^{-}\}$
\end_inset

.
 That 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in\Gamma(A\cup\{b^{-}\})$
\end_inset

 and also that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(b)\geq u(a)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\Gamma(A\cup\{b^{-}\})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The key condition to have a properly defined attention filter is that 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{-}\in\Gamma(A\cup\{b^{-}\})$
\end_inset

.
 Given this, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 is an attention filter.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume contrary to the fact, that 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{-}\notin\Gamma(A\cup\{b^{-}\})$
\end_inset

 this implies that by the attention filter property that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(A)=\Gamma(A\cup\{b^{-}\})$
\end_inset

, by the assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(b)\geq u(a)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\Gamma(A\cup\{b^{-}\})=\Gamma(A)$
\end_inset

 then this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in c(A)$
\end_inset

, which is a contradiction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Random Consideration Sets (Manzini-Mariotti)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a choice set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and an outside alternative 
\begin_inset Formula $o$
\end_inset

 (not in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

).
 The choice set that the consumer faces is 
\begin_inset Formula $X\cup\{o\}$
\end_inset

 and the menu is of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $A=A^{*}\cup\{o\}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $A*\subseteq X$
\end_inset

.
 The collection of menus of the previous form is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A random choice rule is a map 
\begin_inset Formula $p:A\cup\{o\}\times2^{X}\backslash\emptyset\mapsto[0,1]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{a\in A}p(a,A)+p(o,A)=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A random consideration set rule is a random choice rule 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\succ,\gamma}$
\end_inset

 for which there exists a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(\succ,\gamma)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

 is a strict total order on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma:X\mapsto(0,1)$
\end_inset

, such that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{\succ,\gamma}(a,A)=\gamma(a)\prod_{b\in A:b\succ a}(1-\gamma(b))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{D},$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

 (with 
\begin_inset Formula $p(o,A)=\prod_{c\in A}(1-\gamma(c))$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we characterize the model and propose a way to recover both revealed
 preferences and revealed attention.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $Pr(\Gamma_{\gamma}(A)=S)=\prod_{c\in S}\gamma(c)\prod_{c'\in X\setminus S}(1-\gamma(c'))$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $A=\{a,b,c\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}=\{a\},S_{2}=\{b\},S_{3}=\{c\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{4}=\{a,b\},\cdots,S_{8}=\{a,b,c\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{S\subseteq A}Pr(\Gamma_{\gamma}(A)=S)=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $p(a,A)=\sum_{S\subseteq A}1(a=argmax_{x\in\Gamma_{\gamma}(A)}u(x))Pr(\Gamma_{\gamma}(A)=S)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $aRb$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $p(b,A\setminus a)>p(b,A)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also get revealed attention.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(a)=1-p(o,\{a\})$
\end_inset

, equivalently 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(a)=1-\sqrt{\frac{p(o,\{a,b\})p(o,\{a,c\})}{p(o,\{b,c\})}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This holds because 
\begin_inset Formula $p(o,\{a,b\})=(1-\gamma(a))(1-\gamma(b))$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $p(o,\{a,b\})p(o,\{a,c\})=(1-\gamma(a))^{2}(1-\gamma(b))(1-\gamma(c))$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $p(o,\{b,c\})=(1-\gamma(b))(1-\gamma(c))$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{p(o,\{a,b\})p(o,\{a,c\})}{p(o,\{b,c\})}=(1-\gamma(a))^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{p(a,A\cup\{b\})}{p(a,A)}=1-\gamma(b)$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $b\succ a$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Characterization.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
Positivity.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in X\cup\{o\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p(a,A)>0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This axiom rules out the case that some items are never chosen.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
Regularity.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in X$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $p(a,A)\geq p(a,A\cup\{b\})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in D$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now impose the most important axioms.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
(Acyclicity) There is no sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\cdots,a_{n}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\in X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}Ra_{2}\cdots Ra_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}Ra_{1}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq2$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The final axiom is a condition on the outside option.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
(i-Indepence for outside options) 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{p(o,A\setminus\{b\})}{p(o,A)}=\frac{p(o,B\setminus\{b\})}{p(o,B)}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relative probability or odds-ratio of choosing the outside option in
 two menus remains the same when we remove the same object in the two different
 menus.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
The following are equivalent:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(1) The stochastic dataset admits a Random consideration representation
 such that there exists a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(\succ,\gamma)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(a,A)=\gamma(a)\prod_{b\succ a:a\in A}(1-\gamma(b))$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(2) The stochastic dataset satisfies Positivity, Regularity, Acyclicity
 and i-Independence for outside options.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Sketch) The acyclicity of the revealed preference relation allows us to
 recover 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

 on the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The i-Independence conditions allows to recover 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 Under positivity and regularity this is enough to prove that the obtained
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 generate the data.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are going to prove that (1) implies (2).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Positivity follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(a)\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\prod_{b\in A:b\succ a}(1-\gamma(b))=1$
\end_inset

 when the upper contour set of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{\succ}(a)=\{b\in A:b\succ a\}$
\end_inset

 is empty.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $0<p(a,A)=\gamma(a)\prod_{b\succ a:b\in A}(1-\gamma(b))<1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Regularity follows from the fact that if 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in X$
\end_inset

 to a menu 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, when 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

, there are two possibilities: (i) 
\begin_inset Formula $b\succ a$
\end_inset

 (ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succ b$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $p(a,A)=\gamma(a)\prod_{c\in A:c\succ a}(1-\gamma(c))$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $p(a,A\cup\{b\})=\begin{cases}
\gamma(a)\prod_{c\in A:c\succ a}(1-\gamma(c)) & a\succ b\\
\gamma(a)(1-\gamma(b))\prod_{c\in A:c\succ a}(1-\gamma(c)) & b\succ a
\end{cases}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(a,A\cup\{b\})\leq p(a,A)$
\end_inset

 with equality when 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succ b$
\end_inset

 and with inequality if 
\begin_inset Formula $b\succ a$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $aRb$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\iff$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $p(b,A\backslash a)>p(b,A)$
\end_inset

 is acyclic.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That means that there is no cycle, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall n\geq2$
\end_inset

: 
\series bold
there is no
\series default
 sequence of items 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\cdots,a_{n}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}Ra_{2}R\cdots Ra_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}Ra_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By the way of contradiction, we assume that the model is Random consideration
 set such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(a,A)=\gamma(a)\prod_{c\in A:c\succ a}(1-\gamma(c))$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

 strict preferences (transitive) defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

; and at the same time we have a cycle (i.e., there is a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}\cdots a_{n}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}Ra_{2}R\cdots Ra_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}Ra_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}Ra_{2}$
\end_inset

 this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(a_{2},A\backslash a_{1})>p(a_{2},A)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, but this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(a_{2},A\backslash a_{1})=\gamma(a_{2})[\prod_{b\in A:b\succ a_{2}}(1-\gamma(b))]\frac{1}{[1-\gamma(a_{1})]}$
\end_inset

 in other words that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}\succ a_{2}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}Ra_{2}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}\succ a_{2}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The existence of the cycle amounts to the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

 are intransitive, that is a contradiction because rational preferences
 are transitive, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}\succ a_{2}\cdots\succ a_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}\succ a_{1}$
\end_inset

, this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

 is not transitive, which is impossible by definition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Rational Inattention 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Motivating Example
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Imagine you are a monopolist.
 Consider two states of the world: Demand of your output is either 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

good
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

bad
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You get to choose an action: Set the price to be high or low.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Your payoff depends on the action and the state: Quantity sold depends on
 price and demand.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is costly to know the true state of the world.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, you get to learn something about the state before choosing the
 action.
 You could do market research, a focus group.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You can choose what to learn optimally given the problem, the expected payoff
 and the cost of recollecting information.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We model the 
\series bold
choice of information acquisition 
\series default
in an abstract way.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The decision maker chooses an information structure.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
An information structure is: (i) A set of signals to receive.
 (ii) Probability of receiving each signal in each state of the world.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The decision maker then chooses an action conditional on the signal received.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is an optimizing model with additional constraints.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Setup
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\varOmega$
\end_inset

 Objective states of the world (finite)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with prior probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $a:$
\end_inset

 An action, utility depends on the state 
\begin_inset Formula $U(a(\omega))$
\end_inset

 utility of action 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in state 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 set of actions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $A\subset\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 Decision problem finite.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each decision problem 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Choose the information structure 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Set of signals: 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(\pi)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Probability of receiving each signal 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 from each state 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\gamma,\omega)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Choose an action conditional on the signal received 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $c(\gamma)$
\end_inset

 probability distribution over actions given signal 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
In order to maximize 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Expected value of actions taken given posterior beliefs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Minus cost of information 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Formally, the gross value of an information structure is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $G(A,\pi)=$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $max_{C:\Gamma(\pi)\to\Delta A}\sum_{\omega}\mu(\omega)\sum_{\gamma\in\Gamma(\pi)}\pi(\gamma|\omega)\left(\sum_{a\in A}C(a|\gamma)U(a(\omega))\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The cost is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\pi)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{A}\in argmaxG(A,\pi)-K(\pi)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
What about the correct information processing technology.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Choose variance of normal signal (Verrecchia, 1982)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Shannon mutual information cost (Sims, 1988)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Choose from set of available partitions (Ellis, 2012)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Sequential search (McCall, 1970)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Data
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 be a collection of decision problems.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What could we observe?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Standard choice data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $C(A)$
\end_inset

: what is chosen from 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Stochastic choice data:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $P_{A}(a)$
\end_inset

 probability of choosing alternative 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
State dependent stochastic choice data 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $P_{A}(a|\omega)$
\end_inset

 probability of choosing action 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 conditional on state 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Assume that we observe: Prior probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, utilities 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We do not observe: Information structure 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{A}$
\end_inset

, subjective signals 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 and information costs 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What type of stochastic choice data 
\begin_inset Formula $\{D,P\}$
\end_inset

 is consistent with optimal information acquisition?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There exist a cost function 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, for each decision problem 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in D$
\end_inset

 an information structure 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{A}$
\end_inset

 and a choice function 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{A}$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $C_{A}$
\end_inset

 is optimal for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{A}$
\end_inset

 is optimal given 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $C_{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{A}$
\end_inset

 are consistent with 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{A}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{A}(a|\omega)=\sum_{\gamma\in\Gamma(\pi_{A})}\pi_{A}(\gamma|\omega)C_{A}(a|\gamma).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What mistakes are consistent with optimal behavior in the face of information
 costs?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Observing Information Structures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The key observation: State dependent stochastic choice data tells us a lot
 about the information structure a decision maker has used.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume for instance that the decision maker: (i) Chooses each action in
 response to at most one signal.
 (ii) No mixed strategies or one action per signal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then the information structure can be observed directly from state dependent
 stochastic choice.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For each chosen action 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 there is an associated signal 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{a}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The probability of each 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{a}$
\end_inset

 in state 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is the same as the probability of choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi(\gamma^{a}|\omega)=P(a|\omega)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Call 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{r}$
\end_inset

 the revealed information structure.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In general cases, where you have mixed strategies or one action per many
 states, we can still recover the revealed information structure 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{r}$
\end_inset

 but it may not be the true information structure 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
However, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{r}$
\end_inset

 will be a garbling of the true information structure 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There exists a stochastic matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $|\Gamma(\pi)|\times|\Gamma(\pi^{r})|$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 such that if we
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Apply 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For each state 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{i}$
\end_inset

 move to state 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{r,i}$
\end_inset

 with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{ij}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{r}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j}B^{ij}=1\forall j$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{r}(\gamma^{r,j}|\omega)=\sum_{i}B^{ij}\pi(\gamma^{i}|\omega)\forall j$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall Blackwell's Theorem.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G(A,\pi)$
\end_inset

 be the gross value of an information structure 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 in decision problem 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
An information structure 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is sufficient for information structure 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi'$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G(A,\pi)\geq G(A,\pi')\forall A
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Characterizing Rational Inattention
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Choice of act optimal given attentional strategy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Choice of attention strategy optimal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Condition
No Improving Action Switches.
 For every chosen action a
\end_layout

\begin_layout Condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum\mu(\omega)P_{A}(a|\omega)[u(a(\omega))-u(b(\omega))]\ge0,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Condition
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is optimal at all posteriors in which it is chosen.
 It must also be optimal at convex combinations of these posteriors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Condition
No Improving Attention Cycles.
 For an observed sequence of decision problems 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{1}\cdots A^{k}$
\end_inset

 and associated revealed information structures 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{r,1}\cdots\pi^{r,K}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G(A^{1},\pi^{r,1})-G(A^{1},\pi^{r,2})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
+G(A^{2},\pi^{r,2})-G(A^{2},\pi^{r,3})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vdots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
+G(A^{K},\pi^{r,K})-G(A^{K},\pi^{r,1})\geq0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This delivers the representation theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
For any data set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{D,P\}$
\end_inset

 the following two statements are equivalent.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\{D,P\}$
\end_inset

 satisfy NIAS and NIAC
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There exists 
\begin_inset Formula $K:\Pi\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\pi^{A}\}_{A\in D}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{C^{A}\}_{A\in D}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{A}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(\pi^{A})\to A$
\end_inset

 are optimal and generate 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{A}$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in D$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proof requires cyclical consistency again Rockafellar (1970).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Pick some arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0}$
\end_inset

 and define
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T(A)=sup_{all\quad chains\quad A_{0}\quad to\quad A=A_{M}}\sum_{n=0}^{M-1}G(A_{i+1},\pi^{i})-G(A_{i},\pi^{i})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
NIAC implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $T(A_{0})=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also 
\begin_inset Formula $T(A_{0})\geq T(A_{i})+G(A_{o},\pi^{i})-G(A_{i},\pi^{i})$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $T(A_{i})$
\end_inset

 is bounded.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore for any 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i},A_{j}$
\end_inset

 we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T(A_{i})\geq T(A_{j})+G(A_{i},\pi^{j})-G(A_{j},\pi^{j})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta(A_{j})=G(A_{j},\pi^{j})-T(A_{j})$
\end_inset

 we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G(A_{i},\pi^{i})-\theta(A_{i})\geq G(A_{i},\pi^{j})-\theta(A_{j})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also get the following property for free:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Information structures that are more Blackwell informative are weakly more
 expensive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Say 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{A}$
\end_inset

in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is sufficient for 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{B}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G(B,\pi^{B})-K(\pi^{B})\geq G(B,\pi^{A})-K(\pi^{A})\implies
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $K(\pi^{A})-K(\pi^{B})\geq G(B,\pi^{A})-G(B,\pi^{B})\geq0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the last inequality is due to the Blackwell's Theorem 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G(B,\pi^{A})\geq G(B,\pi^{B}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Recovering Costs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Say 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{r,A}$
\end_inset

 is the revealed attention strategy in decision problem 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming weak monotonicity, it must be that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K(\pi^{r,A})-K(\pi)\leq G(A,\pi^{r,A})-G(A,\pi)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{r,B}$
\end_inset

 is used in decision problem 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 then we can bound relative costs 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G(B,\pi^{r,A})-G(B,\pi^{r,B})\leq K(\pi^{r,A})-K(\pi^{r,B})\leq G(A,\pi^{r,A})-G(A,\pi^{r,B}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can get tighter bounds using chains of observations (Rockafellar 1970).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Rational Inattention with Shannon Information Costs 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Shannon Entropy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Shannon Entropy is a measure of how much missing information there is in
 a probability distribution.
 In other words:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How much we do not know, or how much we would learn from resolving the uncertain
ty.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 that takes the value 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x_{i})$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\cdots,n$
\end_inset

 defined as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H(X)=E[-ln(p(x_{i}))]=-\sum_{i}p(x_{i})ln(p_{i}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Shannon Entropy has the following properties:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Depends only on the probability distribution: 
\begin_inset Formula $H(X)=H(p)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Maximized at a uniform probability distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Unaffected by adding zero probability state 
\begin_inset Formula $H(\{p_{1},\cdots,p_{M}\})=H(\{p_{1},\cdots,p_{M},0\})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Additive (Constant Returns) 
\begin_inset Formula $H(X,Y)=H(X)+\sum_{x}p(x)H(Y|x)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
How much you learn from observing 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, plus how much you additionally learn from observing 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For independent variables 
\begin_inset Formula $H(X)+H(Y)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This is the most restrictive condition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The entropy must be of the form (Khinchin 1957)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H(X)=\sum_{i}p(x_{i})ln(p_{i}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Entropy and Information Costs: Mutual Information
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The notion of Mutual Information 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I(X,Y)=\sum_{x}\sum_{y}p(x,y)log\frac{p(x,y)}{p(x)p(y)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a measure of how much information one variable tells you about another.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $X,Y$
\end_inset

 are independent then 
\begin_inset Formula $I(X,Y)=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mutual information can be written in the following way:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I(X,Y)=H(X)-E[H(X|Y)]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=-\sum_{x}p(x)lnp(x)+\sum_{y}p(y)\sum_{x}p(x|y)lnP(x|y).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the difference between the entropy of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and the expected entropy of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 once 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is known.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can use this to formulate the attention cost:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $K(\mu,\pi)=\lambda[H(\mu)-E[H(\gamma)]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\lambda\left(-\sum_{\omega\in\Omega}\mu(\omega)ln\mu(\omega)+\sum_{\gamma\in\Gamma(\pi)}\pi(\gamma)\sum_{\omega\in\Omega}\gamma(\omega)ln\gamma(\omega)\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For convenience we call 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 the posterior belief generated by signal 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This costs can be justified by information theory.
 Check Thomas book for details.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Shannon entropy is strictly concave, so negative entropy is strictly convex.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Say we choose a signal structure with two posteriors 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma,\gamma'$
\end_inset

 it must be that.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(\gamma)\gamma+P(\gamma')\gamma'=\mu
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
so
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(\gamma)H(\gamma)+P(\gamma')H(\gamma')<H(P(\gamma)\gamma+P(\gamma')\gamma')=H(\mu)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
so the cost of learning something is always positive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Solving Rational Inattention Models.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The general approach is to ignore the information structure, instead focus
 on the joint distribution of the choice variable and the state.
 We can do this because the optimal strategy is going to be well-behaved
 (one action per one signal, and no mixed strategies).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Example (Matejka and McKay 2015) continuous state space, finite action space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 is the set of all state contingent stochastic choice functions for some
 state space 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 and set of acts 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Remember 
\begin_inset Formula $P(a|\omega)$
\end_inset

 is the probability of choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in state 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mutual information between probability of choices and the objective
 state 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I(A,\Omega)=H(A)-H(A|\Omega).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The decision problem of the agent is to choose 
\begin_inset Formula $P\in\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 to maximize
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{a\in A}\int_{\omega}u(a(\omega))P(a|\omega)\mu(d\omega)-
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda\left[-\sum_{a\in A}\int_{\omega}P(a|\omega)lnP(a|\omega)\mu(d\omega)+\sum_{a\in A}P(a)lnP(a)\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
subject to 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{a\in A}P(a|\omega)=1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $+\int_{\omega}\rho(\omega)[\sum_{a\in A}P(a|\omega)-1]\mu(d\omega).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
almost surely.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $P(a)$
\end_inset

 is the unconditional probability of choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(\int_{\omega}P(a|\omega)\mu(d\omega)=P(a))$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that another constraint which we will ignore for now is 
\begin_inset Formula $P(a|\omega)\geq0\forall a,\omega$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First order conditions with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $P(a|\omega)$
\end_inset

 assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $>0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(a(\omega))-\rho(\omega)+\lambda[lnP(a)+1-lnP(a|\omega)-1]=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that this is a convex problem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(a|\omega)=P(a)exp[\frac{u(a(\omega))-\rho(\omega)}{\lambda}]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Plug this into 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{a'\in A}p(a'|\omega)=1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To obtain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
-
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(a|\omega)=\frac{P(a)exp[u(a(\omega))/\lambda]}{\sum_{c\in A}P(c)exp[u(c(\omega))/\lambda]}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similar in form to the logistic random choice.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If alternatives are ex-ante identical this is logistic choice.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Otherwise choice probabilities are 'warped/distorted' by 
\begin_inset Formula $P(a)$
\end_inset

 which contains information on the prior value of each option.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As costs go to zero, deterministically pick the best option in that state.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As costs go to infinity deterministically pick the best option ex-ante.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
An Important Caveat
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The MM (Matejka-McKay) conditions ignore the constraint
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(a|\omega)\ge0\forall a,\omega
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We need to know which acts will be chosen with positive probability.
 Typically there will be many acts not chosen at the optimum (Matejka and
 Sims, 2010).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There will be many solutions to the necessary conditions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ideally, we would like necessary and sufficient conditions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Necessary and Sufficient Conditions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $z(a(\omega))$
\end_inset

 be the normalized utilities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z(a,\omega)=exp\left\{ \frac{u(a,\omega)}{\lambda}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the MM conditions are 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(a|\omega)=\frac{P(a)z(a,\omega)}{\sum_{c\in A}P(c)z(c,\omega)}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is consistent with rational inattention with mutual information if and
 only if 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{\omega}\left[\frac{\mu(\omega)z(a,\omega)}{\sum_{c\in A}P(c)z(c,\omega)}\right]\leq1\forall a\in A
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{\omega}\left[\frac{\mu(\omega)z(a,\omega)}{\sum_{c\in A}P(c)z(c,\omega)}\right]=1\forall a\in A,P(a)>0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(a|\omega)=\frac{P(a)z(a,\omega)}{\sum_{c\in A}P(c)z(c,\omega)}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Identify the correct unconditional choice probabilities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Consideration sets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Corner solutions induce a consideration set.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Choose from a set of acts 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\{a_{1},\cdots,a_{N}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Only one of these goods is of high quality:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $u_{h}$
\end_inset

 utility of the high quality good, 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{l}$
\end_inset

 utility of low quality good, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{i}$
\end_inset

 prior probability that good 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is the high quality good.
 Without loss of generality 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{1}\geq\mu_{2}\cdots\geq\mu_{N}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution is a cut-off strategy in prior probabilities.
 There exists 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 such that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{i}>c\implies i
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
chosen with positive probability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{i}<c\implies i
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
never chosen and nothing is learned about their quality.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This forms endogenously a consideration set.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=\frac{exp(\frac{u_{h}}{\lambda})}{exp(\frac{u_{l}}{\lambda})}-1$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

additional
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 utility from high act.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Search the best 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 alternatives where 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 solves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{K}>\frac{\sum_{k=1}^{K}\mu_{k}}{K+\delta}\geq\mu_{K+1}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can use equality constraints to solve for unconditional choice probabilities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(a_{i})=\frac{\mu(\omega_{i})(K+\delta)-\sum_{k=1}^{K}\mu(\omega_{k})}{\delta\sum_{k=1}^{K}\mu(\omega_{k})}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MM conditions solve for conditional choice probabilities 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(b|b=u_{h})=\frac{P(b)\delta}{\sum_{c\in A}p(c)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The MM necessary conditions could be solved for many possible consideration
 sets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Choosing any option with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 will solve the necessary conditions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For any set 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 with worst alternative 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{C}$
\end_inset

 there is a solution to the necessary conditions if 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\mu_{C}}{\sum_{k\in C}\mu_{k}}>\frac{1}{|C|+\delta}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These conditions do not reference unchosen actions.
 They do not determine whether higher utility could be obtained with a different
 consideration set.
 This is the advantage of the sufficient conditions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Given a decision problem 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mu,A)\in\Gamma\times\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 a set of posteriors are rationally inattentive if and only if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Invariant Likelihood Ratio (ILR) Equations for Chosen Acts: given 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in\Omega$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\gamma^{a}(\omega)}{z(a(\omega))}=\frac{\gamma^{b}(\omega)}{z(b(\omega))}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Likelihood Ratio Inequalities for Unchosen Acts: given act 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 chosen with positive probability and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in A$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{\omega\in\Omega}\left[\frac{\gamma^{a}(\omega)}{z(a(\omega))}\right]z(b(\omega))\leq1.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Search and Satisficing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Satisficing model (Simon, 1955) was an early model of consideration set
 formation.
 This is a very simple and widely used model:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The decision maker (DM) is faced with a set of alternatives 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The DM searches through 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 one by one.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
At each step in the search the DM compares the item at hand using a utility
 function and then compares it with a threshold.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the item is above the threshold then the DM stops the search and picks
 the item.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If all objects are searched and there is no satisficing items then the DM
 chooses the best alternative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Satisficing as Optimal Stopping
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 items from a set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A utility 
\begin_inset Formula $u:X\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $f:$
\end_inset

 the decision makers beliefs about the value of each option.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A per object search cost 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At any point the DM has two options.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Stop searching, and choose the best alternative so far seen.
 (Search with recall).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Search another item and pay the cost 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is very familiar from labor economics.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can solve for the optimal strategy by backwards induction.
 Choice when there is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 more object to search and current best alternative has utility 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{u}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Stop searching: 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{u}-(M-1)k$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Search the final item:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{-\infty}^{\overline{u}}\overline{u}f(u)du+\int_{\overline{u}}^{\infty}uf(u)du-Mk.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Continue searching if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{u}-(M-1)k\leq
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{-\infty}^{\overline{u}}\overline{u}f(u)du+\int_{\overline{u}}^{\infty}uf(u)du-Mk.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Implying
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k\leq\int_{\overline{u}}^{\infty}(u-\overline{u})f(u)du.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Value of RHS decreasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{u}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Implies cutoff strategy: search continues if 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{u}>u^{*}$
\end_inset

 solving:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k=\int_{u^{*}}^{\infty}(u-u^{*})f(u)du.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The strategy is the same if there are 2 items remaining:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{u}<u^{*}$
\end_inset

 search will continue
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{u}>u^{*}$
\end_inset

 search will stop.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The optimal strategy is the same for any 
\begin_inset Formula $nth$
\end_inset

 items remaining and it is satisficing:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Find 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{*}$
\end_inset

 that solves:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k=\int_{u^{*}}^{\infty}(u-u^{*})f(u)du.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Continue searching until find an object with 
\begin_inset Formula $u>u^{*}$
\end_inset

, then stop.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $u^{*}$
\end_inset

 decreasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
increasing in variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Unaffected by the size of the choice set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This comes from optimization not from satisficing model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The fact that we can solve for this search problem depends on its simple
 structure.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Cost depending on the size of the menu, multiple attributes, exploration,
 possibility of not searching.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Testing Satisficing: The Problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If you use choice data alone it is difficult to test because its empirical
 implications are indistinguishable from preference maximization.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the search order changes between choice sets, then any behavior can be
 rationalized.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We need to: 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Add more assumptions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Enrich the data: Stochastic choice data: Aguiar, Boccardi and Dean (2016).
 Search order observed from internet data [De los Santos, Hortacsu, and
 Wildenbeast, 2012].
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Relax assumptions? Aguiar and Kimya (2017).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Choice Process Data
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
We will start by considering possible data enrichment, from Caplin, Dean
 and Martin (2012), called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

choice process
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 data.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Records how choice changes with contemplation time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $C(A)$
\end_inset

: Standard choice data -choice from set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $C_{A}(t):$
\end_inset

 Choice process data- choice made from the set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 after contemplation time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Easy to collect such data in the laboratory, and it is possible to look
 for this in the wild possibly using the internet.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
First, introduce some notation:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

: Finite grand choice set.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

: Not-empty subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $Z\in\{Z_{t}\}_{t}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

: Sequences of elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Z}$
\end_inset

 set of sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Z}_{A}\subset\mathcal{Z}$
\end_inset

: set of sequences s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{t}\subset A\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A Choice Process Data Set 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,C)$
\end_inset

 comprises of:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
finite set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
choice function 
\begin_inset Formula $C:\mathcal{X}\to\mathcal{Z}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
such that 
\begin_inset Formula $C(A)\in\mathcal{Z}_{A}\forall A\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $C_{A}(t):$
\end_inset

 choice made from set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 after comtemplation time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Characterizing the Satisficing Model
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
1.
 Search is alternative based.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The DM searches through items in choice set sequentially.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Completely understands each item before moving on to the next.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
2.
 Stopping is due to a fixed reservation rule.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Subjects have a fixed reservation utility level.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Stop searching if and only if the DM finds an item with a utility above
 that level.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
The DM has a utility 
\begin_inset Formula $u:X\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and a search correspondence:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S:\mathcal{X}\to\mathcal{Z},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{A}(t)\subseteq S_{A}(t+s)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Such that the DM always chooses best option of those searched
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{A}(t)=argmax_{x\in S_{A}(t)}u(x).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Expected Utility and Non-Expected Utility Models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Dataset or Primitives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 to be a set of finite alternatives.
 We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $p:Z\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a probability distribution on 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $p(z)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{z\in Z}p(x)=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 be the set of probability distributions on 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For any 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in Z$
\end_inset

 let 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{z}\in\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 be the Dirach distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{z}(z)=1$
\end_inset

.
 This is also called degenerate lotteries.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For any two probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $p,q\in\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 and a number 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 we define a third probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha p+(1-\alpha)q\in\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 as follows: 
\begin_inset Formula $[\alpha p+(1-\alpha)q](z)=\alpha p(z)+(1-\alpha)q(z)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We observe a choice structure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B},C$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}\subseteq\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a choice correspondence.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider a preference relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
we say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 has a expected utility representation if there exists a (Bernoulli) utility
 function 
\begin_inset Formula $u:Z\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that the function 
\begin_inset Formula $U(p):=\sum_{z\in Z}u(z)p(z)$
\end_inset

 represents 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Bernoulli utility is bounded and continuous and is defined over prices
 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Independence Axiom
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 are rational.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
(Independence Axiom) For all 
\begin_inset Formula $p,q,r\in\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p\succeq q$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha p+(1-\alpha)r\succeq\alpha q+(1-\alpha)r.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The other axiom that we need is more technical 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
(Mixture continuity) For all 
\begin_inset Formula $p,q,r\in\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $p\succ q\succ r$
\end_inset

, then the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\alpha\in[0,1]|\alpha p+(1-\alpha)r\succ q\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\alpha\in[0,1]|q\succ\alpha p+(1-\alpha)r\}$
\end_inset

 are open in 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Representation Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
The preference relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 satisfies the Independence Axiom and Mixture continuity if and only if
 there exists a utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $u:Z\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p\succeq q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{z\in Z}u(z)p(z)\geq\sum_{z\in Z}u(z)q(z)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Allais Paradox
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is finite in fact 
\begin_inset Formula $N=3$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Tabular
<lyxtabular version="3" rows="2" columns="3">
<features tabularvalignment="middle">
<column alignment="center" valignment="top">
<column alignment="center" valignment="top">
<column alignment="center" valignment="top">
<row>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" bottomline="true" leftline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
First Prize
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" bottomline="true" leftline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Second Price
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" bottomline="true" leftline="true" rightline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Third Price
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
</row>
<row>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" bottomline="true" leftline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
2.5 millions
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" bottomline="true" leftline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
0.5 millions
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" bottomline="true" leftline="true" rightline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
</row>
</lyxtabular>

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two choice sets:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}=(0,1,0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}'=(0.10,0.89,0.01)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}=(0,0.11,0.89)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}'=(0.10,0,0.90)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some individuals choose 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}\succ L_{1}'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}'\succ L_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is inconsistent with expected utility.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}\succ L_{1}'$
\end_inset

 then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{0.5}>(0.10)u_{2.5}+(0.89)u_{.5}+(0.01)u_{0}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Adding, 
\begin_inset Formula $(0.89)u_{0}-(0.89)u_{0.5}$
\end_inset

 to both sides we get,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(0.11)u_{0.5}+(0.89)u_{0}>(0.1)u_{2.5}+(0.9)u_{0},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}\succ L_{2}'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Betweenness 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This follows Stralecki notes.
 The following model is a very simple relaxation of the independence axiom,
 and therefore of expected utility to deal with the Allais Paradox.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first model allows to relax the expected utility assumption that indifferenc
e curves in the simplex are straight parallel lines.
 Now, we are going to keep linearity but allow for fanning out.
 This is what one observes in the Allais paradox.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 be any set and 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

 be defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

.
 The main axiom is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
(Betweenness) If 
\begin_inset Formula $p\succ q$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $[p\sim q]$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $p\succ\alpha p+(1-\alpha)q\succ q$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $[p\sim\alpha p+(1-\alpha)q\sim q]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The intuition of the new Betweenness axiom is that a mixture of a better
 and worse elements is better than the worse element but worse than the
 better.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also need a technical axioms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
Calibration Continuity.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $p,q,r\in\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $p\succeq q\succeq r$
\end_inset

, then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $q\sim\alpha p+(1-\alpha)r$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also assume the existence of a best and worst elements.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
Best and Worst.
 There exists 
\begin_inset Formula $b,w\in Z$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{b}\succeq p\succeq\delta_{w}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The representation theorem is the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(Dekel, 1986) A weak order on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 satisfies Betweenness, Calibration Continuity and Best and Worst if and
 only if there exists a function 
\begin_inset Formula $u:Z\times[0,1]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $u(b,v)=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u(w,v)=0$
\end_inset

, continuous in the second argument, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U(p)$
\end_inset

, is defined implicitly as the unique 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 that solves 
\begin_inset Formula $v=\sum_{z\in Z}u(z,v)p(z)$
\end_inset

 represents 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This model allows that the indifference curve for each lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 looks as if it is the indifference curve of an EU preference.
 So there must be a Bernoulli utility that represents that EU preference
 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\cdot,U(p))$
\end_inset

 is what we are looking for.
 The key is that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\cdot,U(p))$
\end_inset

 will change as we change 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 A particular version of this model that is very popular is called Disappointmen
t Aversion.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Disappointment Aversion 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For some 
\begin_inset Formula $b,w\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $w<b$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=[w,b]$
\end_inset

 be the set of monetary prizes.
 We consider again 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

.
 The agent likes more than less.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
More Money is Better.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in Z$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x>y$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{x}\succ d_{y}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, for each lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 we look at prizes that are better and worse than 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $B(p)=\{z\in Z:\delta_{z}\succeq p\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W(p)=\{z\in Z:p\succeq\delta_{z}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we look at the lotteries concentrated in 
\begin_inset Formula $B(p)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W(p)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula ${\bf B}(p)=\{q\in\Delta(Z):supp(q)\subseteq B(p)\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula ${\bf W}(p)=\{q\in\Delta(Z):supp(q)\subseteq W(p)\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,q,r$
\end_inset

 is called the elation/disappointment decomposition of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in{\bf B}(p)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in{\bf W}(p)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha q+(1-\alpha)r=p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $D(p)$
\end_inset

 denote the set of elation/disappointment decomposition of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 (there may be multiple ones).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 has a disappointment aversion representation if there exists a continuous
 utility 
\begin_inset Formula $u:Z\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\in(-1,\infty)$
\end_inset

 such that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U(p)=\frac{\alpha}{1+(1-\alpha)\beta}\sum_{z\in Z}u(z)q(z)+\left(1-\frac{\alpha}{1+(1-\alpha)\beta}\right)\sum_{z\in Z}u(z)r(z),
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
represents 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $(\alpha,q,r)\in D(p)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Probability Weighting and Rank Dependent Expected Utility.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Kahneman and Tversky's Prospect Theory has 4 elements: reference points,
 reflection effect, and loss aversion.
 We consider now only probability weighting.
 The main idea is that instead of computing 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{z\in Z}u(z)p(z)$
\end_inset

 the decision maker does not take the probabilities at face value but instead
 transforms then by some monotone and continuous function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:[0,1]\to[0,1]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(0)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(1)=1$
\end_inset

 and computes 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{z\in Z}u(z)\phi(p(z))$
\end_inset

.
 Adding this new (infinite dimensional) parameter helps us to account for
 things like the Allais Paradox, Common Ratio Paradox.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But this model has a big problem it violates First-Order Stochastic Dominance.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{p}$
\end_inset

 denote the cdf of a lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 first order stochastically dominates 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{q}(t)\geq F_{p}(t)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in Z$
\end_inset

, it is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $p\geq_{1}q$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following property is observed commonly in experiments.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
(Monotonicity) If 
\begin_inset Formula $p\geq_{1}q$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $p\succeq q$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expected utility is monotone if the Bernoulli utility is weakly increasing.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)=x^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u(z)=z$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\frac{1}{2}\delta_{1}+\frac{1}{2}\delta_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{z}u(z)\phi(p(z))=\frac{3}{4}$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand if 
\begin_inset Formula $q=\delta_{1}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{z}u(z)\phi(q(z))=1$
\end_inset

, a violation of FOSD monotonicity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To fix this problem we have to compute the expectation in different ways.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\circ p$
\end_inset

 is not necessarily a probability distribution (it may not add-up to 1).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we use the cdf of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{p}$
\end_inset

 we can transform it to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\circ F_{p}$
\end_inset

, this is a cdf of other lottery.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
(Rank dependent expected utility) Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $p=p_{1}\delta_{z_{1}}+p_{2}\delta_{z_{2}}+p_{3}\delta_{z_{3}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{1}<z_{2}<z_{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}+p_{2}+p_{3}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Now we can compute the CDF and obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\circ F_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 The new lottery is 
\begin_inset Formula $q=q_{1}\delta_{z_{1}}+q_{2}\delta_{z2}+q_{3}\delta_{z3}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=\phi(p_{1})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}=\phi(p_{1}+p_{2})-\phi(p_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{3}=1-\phi(p_{1}+p_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(z_{1})\phi(p_{1})+u(z_{2})[\phi(p_{1}+p_{2})-\phi(p_{1})]+u(z_{3})[1-\phi(p_{1}+p_{2})].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
The weights that corresponds to a prize 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the rank of the prize.
 Hence the name Rank Dependent Utility.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are ready to define the model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Rank Dependent Expected Utility) A preference 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 has a RDEU representation if there exist functions 
\begin_inset Formula $u:Z\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and a continuous and increasing function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:[0,1]\to[0,1]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(0)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(1)=1$
\end_inset

 such that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{Z}u(z)d(\phi\circ F_{p})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
represents 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is linear.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=[0,1]$
\end_inset

 and we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define for 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 the decumulative distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{p}(t)=p(\{z>t\})$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{p}$
\end_inset

 is noincreasing, right-continuous, and 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{p}(1)=0$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 denote the set of all such functions.
 Note that for each 
\begin_inset Formula $G\in\Gamma$
\end_inset

 there exists a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $G=G_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 So we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $p\succ q$
\end_inset

 interchangeably with 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{p}\succ G_{q}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}$
\end_inset

 continuity.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\{q:q\succ p\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{q:p\succ q\}$
\end_inset

 are open in the topology generated by the 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}$
\end_inset

 metric, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(p,q)=\int_{0}^{1}|G_{p}(t)-G_{q}(t)|dt$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main axiom is going to be the usual independence axiom but applied to
 the inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
For any 
\begin_inset Formula $G\in\Gamma$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $G^{-1}(x)=inf\{t:G(t)\leq x\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is like the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

quantiles
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of decumulative distributions.
 Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $G^{-1}\in\Gamma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(G^{-1})^{-1}=G$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
For any 
\begin_inset Formula $G,H\in\Gamma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha G\boxplus(1-\alpha)H=(\alpha G^{-1}+(1-\alpha)H^{-1})^{-1}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally we state the main axiom.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
Dual Independence.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $p,q,r\in\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 and all 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{p}\succeq G_{q}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha G_{p}\boxplus(1-\alpha)G_{r}\succeq\alpha G_{q}\boxplus(1-\alpha)G_{r}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are ready to state the main result.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
A weak order 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 satisfies Dual Independence, L1 Continuity and Monotonicity (FOSD) if and
 only if it has a RDEU representation with 
\begin_inset Formula $u(z)=z$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's understand what risk aversion means here.
 1.
 You like the Expected Mean Value of a lottery more than the lottery itself,
 2.
 you don't like mean preserving spreads.
 For EU this both coincide and correspond to concavity of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
 For RDEU the two concepts are different.
 For the second definition, disliking mean preserving spreads mean that
 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 are concave.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Prospect Theory and Reference Dependence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will introduce a model that abstracts away from probability weighting
 and introduces decreasing sensitivity and loss aversion.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assign a utility to a monetary gamble 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 with a reference level of income 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U(p,w)=\sum_{x\in X}p(x)v(x-w)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is a value function applied to the difference between a price and the reference
 of wealth.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rather than assessing the final level of wealth the DM assess gains and
 losses from 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Assumption
The marginal impact of gains and losses is decreasing as one moves away
 from the reference point (i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $v'(x)$
\end_inset

 increasing for 
\begin_inset Formula $x<0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v''(x)>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $v'(x)$
\end_inset

 decreasing for 
\begin_inset Formula $x>0$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $v''(x)>0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The value function 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is concave in the gain domain and convex in the loss domain.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This explains the reflection effect by imposing that the DM is risk avoiding
 in the loss domain.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Reflection Effect.
 Two groups of subjects with different choices.
 Set up for each choice is the same.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

An outbreak of a disease is expected to cause 600 deaths in the US.
 Two mutually exclusive programs are expected to yield the following results.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Choice A.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
400 people will die.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $1/3$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 people will die, while 
\begin_inset Formula $2/3$
\end_inset

 600 people will die.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Choice B
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
200 people will be saved
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
with 
\begin_inset Formula $1/3$
\end_inset

, all 
\begin_inset Formula $600$
\end_inset

 will be saved, 
\begin_inset Formula $2/3$
\end_inset

 none will be saved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Choice A, 
\begin_inset Formula $78\%$
\end_inset

 chose 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Choice 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $28\%$
\end_inset

 chose 2.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Interpretation: People are more risk averse in the gain domain that in the
 loss domain.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Loss Aversion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the central assumptions in behavioral economics is that: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Losses loom larger than gains
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The aggravation of losing 
\begin_inset Formula $\$5$
\end_inset

 is greater than equivalent joy of gaining 
\begin_inset Formula $\$5$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Operationalized by assuming that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x>0$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-v(-x)>v(x)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One specific case:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-v(-x)=\lambda v(x).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What are the empirical implications of this assumption.
 None if we only observe gains or losses.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have implications for cases where we have mixes of gambles with gains
 or losses.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In case where 
\begin_inset Formula $v(x)=\alpha x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-v(-x)=\lambda v(x)$
\end_inset

 we have a DM that is risk neutral for gains and losses and risk averse
 for mixed gambles.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More generally risk aversion for mixed gambles is higher than one would
 expect having observed preferences in the gain and loss domain.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Random Expected Utility and Catious Expected Utility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Random Expected Utility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N=\{1,\cdots,n+1\}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be the set of outcomes.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $P=\{x\in\mathbb{R}_{+}^{n+1}|\sum_{i=1}^{n+1}x^{i}=1\}$
\end_inset

 be the set of lotteries.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 be the set of Borel algebra of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 be the set of all finite subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 is the set of choice sets.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi$
\end_inset

 be set set of all probabilities measures on the measurable space 
\begin_inset Formula $(P,\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in\mathbb{R}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

, I have 
\begin_inset Formula $(u^{1}-u^{n+1},\cdots,u^{n}-u^{n+1})\cdot x=\sum_{i=1}^{n+1}u^{i}x_{i}-u_{n+1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
\begin_inset Formula $u\cdot x\geq u\cdot y$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $(u^{1}-u^{n+1},\cdots,u^{n}-u^{n+1})\cdot x\geq(u^{1}-u^{n+1},\cdots,u^{n}-u^{n+1})\cdot y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can normalize the set of utilities as 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\{u\in\mathbb{R}^{n+1}|u^{n+1}=0\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For any 
\begin_inset Formula $D\in\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in D$
\end_inset

 define
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $N(D,x)=\{u\in U|u\cdot x\geq u\cdot y\quad\forall y\in D\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $N^{+}(D,x)=\{u\in U|u\cdot x>u\cdot y\quad\forall y\in D\setminus x\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N(D,x)$
\end_inset

 is the set of utilities such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is an optimal choice from 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{+}(D,x)$
\end_inset

 is the set of utilities such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is the unique optimal choice for 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be the smallest algebra that contains 
\begin_inset Formula $N(D,x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(D,x)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A random utility function is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu:\mathcal{F}\to[0,1]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(U)=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu(F\cup F')=\mu(F)+\mu(F')
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
if 
\begin_inset Formula $F\cap F'=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F,F'\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 The RUF is countable additive if 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{\infty}\mu(F_{i})=\mu(\cup_{i=1}^{\infty}F_{i})$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a countable collection of pairwise disjoint sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\cup_{i=1}^{\infty}F_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A random utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is regular if in every decision problem with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, the realized utility function has a unique maximizer.
 Formally, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is regular if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(\cup_{x\in D}N^{+}(D,x))=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $D\in\mathcal{D}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Regular utilities give zero probability to the utilities that allow ties.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A random choice function 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is called regular random expected utility function if there exists a regular
 random utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho^{D}(x)=\mu(N(D,x))$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $D\in\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in P$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is countably additive if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is countably additive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are ready to state the preliminary theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
For a random choice function 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, if there exists two regular random utility functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu'$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(N(D,x))=\rho^{D}(x)=\mu'(N(D,x))$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $D\in\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in P$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=\mu'$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For any 
\begin_inset Formula $D,D'\in\mathcal{D},$
\end_inset

 the Hausdorff Distance between 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D'$
\end_inset

 is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{h}(D,D')=max\{max_{x\in D}min_{x'\in D'}||x-x'||,max_{x'\in D'}min_{x\in D}||x-x'||\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For all 
\begin_inset Formula $D,D'\subset\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda D+(1-\lambda)D'=\{\lambda x+(1-\lambda)y|x\in D,y\in D'\}\in\mathcal{D},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the mixture is the probability mixture.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The RCR 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Mixture continuous if 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho^{\alpha D+(1-\alpha)D'}$
\end_inset

 is continuous in 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $D,D'\in\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
continuous if 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho:\mathcal{D}\to\Pi$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
monotone if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in D\subset D'$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho^{D'}(x)\leq\rho^{D}(x)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
linear if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho^{\lambda D+(1-\lambda)\{y\}}(\lambda x+(1-\lambda)y)=\rho^{D}(x).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
extreme if 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho^{D}(extD)=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main result is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
The RCR 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is mixture continuous, monotone, linear and extreme if and only if it is
 a regular random expected utility function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
The RCR 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is continuous, montone, linear and extreme if it is a countably additive
 regular random utility function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally we have an identification result.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is monotone, linear, and extreme then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in D$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x'\in D'$
\end_inset

 and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N(D,x)=N(D',x')\implies\rho^{D}(x)=\rho^{D'}(x').
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Cautious Expected Utility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Many violations of the independence axiom of the expected utility can be
 traced to the subjects' attraction to risk-free prospects.
 The key axiom here is negative certainty independence (Dillenberger, 2010)
 formalizes this tendency.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The resulting representation is an agent that is unsure about how to evaluate
 a given lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, instead, she has in mind a set of possible utility functions over outcomes
 and displays a catious behavior.
 She computes the certainty equivalent of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 with respect to each possible utility function in the set and picks the
 smallest one.
 The set of utilities is unique in a well defined sense.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
Weak Monotonicity.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in[w,b]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x\geq y$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{x}\succeq\delta_{y}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
Negative Certainty Independence NCI: For each 
\begin_inset Formula $p,q\in\Delta$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in[w,b]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\succeq\delta_{x}\implies\lambda p+(1-\lambda)q\succeq\lambda\delta_{x}+(1-\lambda)q.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
NCI states that if the sure outcome 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is not enough to compensate the DM for the risky prospect 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, then mixing it with any other lottery, thus eliminating its certainty
 appeal, will not result in the mixture of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 being more attractive than the corresponding mixture of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{p}$
\end_inset

 the certainty equivalent of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 might not be enough to compensate for 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 when part of a mixture.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this sense, NCI captures the certainty effect (Kahneman and Tversky,
 1979).
 But it is more broad since it applies to lotteries with more than two outcomes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We say that a function 
\begin_inset Formula $V:\Delta\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 represents 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $p\succeq q$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $V(p)\geq V(q)$
\end_inset

.
 Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{U}$
\end_inset

 the set of continuous and strictly increasing functions 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $[w,b]$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We endow 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{U}$
\end_inset

 with the topology induced by the supnorm.
 For each lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and function 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in\mathcal{U}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{p}(v)$
\end_inset

 denotes the expected utility of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

.
 The certainty equivalent of lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 calculated using the function 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is thus 
\begin_inset Formula $c(p,v)=v^{-1}(E_{p}(v))\in[w,b]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 be a binary relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{W}$
\end_inset

 be a a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{U}$
\end_inset

.
 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{W}$
\end_inset

 is a catious expected utility representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 if and only if the function 
\begin_inset Formula $V:\Delta\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 defined by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(p)=inf_{v\in\mathcal{W}}c(p,v)\forall p\in\Delta
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
represents 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

.
 We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{W}$
\end_inset

 is a continuous catious expected utility respresentation if and only if
 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is also continuous.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main result is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 be a binary relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

.
 The following statements are equivalent:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(i) The relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 satisfies Weak Order, Continuity, Weak Monotonicity, and NCI.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(ii) There exists a continuous catious expected utility representation of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can now talk about attitutes towards risk.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is risk averse if 
\begin_inset Formula $p\succeq q$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is a mean preserving spread of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are ready to state the second main result.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 be a binary relation that satisfies Weak Order, Continuity, Weak Monotonity,
 and NCI.
 The following statements are true:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(i) The relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is risk averse if and only if every 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in\mathcal{W}$
\end_inset

 is concave.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(ii) The relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is risk seeking if and only if each 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in\mathcal{W}$
\end_inset

 is convex.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Ambiguity and Subjective Probability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have only dealt with risk, i.e., with objective probabilities.
 However, such objective probabilities may not be always available to the
 DM.
 There are many situations where there is a one-shot even that is uncertain
 (e.g., elections, wars, buying a house).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We need a model to capture that.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The primitives are state space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, outcomes 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

, the set of acts 
\begin_inset Formula $Z^{S}$
\end_inset

 (functions from 
\begin_inset Formula $s\to z$
\end_inset

), and preference relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 over some subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z^{S}$
\end_inset

.
 Typical elements are 
\begin_inset Formula $E,F\subseteq S$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in Z$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g,h\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 States are assumed to be mutually exclusive and collectively exhaustive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first model is called subjective probability, because the DM has a belief
 over the probabilities of states and a preference over actions conditional
 on those states.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A preference 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 has a Subjective Expected Utility (SEU) representation if there exist a
 probability measure 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and a Bernolli utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $u:Z\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is represented by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(f)=\int_{s\in S}u(f(s))dP(s).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Uppercase probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 are used to denote a subjective probability.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Savage Axiomatization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will study the axiomatization of SEU due to Savage.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
An act 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is simple or finite ranged iff the set 
\begin_inset Formula $f(S)$
\end_inset

 is finite.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We define now the following operation (splicing):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
For any two acts 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and any event 
\begin_inset Formula $E\subseteq S$
\end_inset

 define an act 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{E}g$
\end_inset

 such that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{E}g(s)=\begin{cases}
f(s) & s\in E\\
g(s) & otherwise
\end{cases}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We say that an event is null iff 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{E}h\sim g_{E}h$
\end_inset

 for all acts 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g,h\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
Preferences 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 over acts induce preferences over prizes as follows.
 We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq y$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in Z$
\end_inset

 iff the act that gives 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in every state is preferred to the act that gives 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
P1-Weak Order.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is complete and transitive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
P2-Sure Thing Principle.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{E}g\succ h_{E}g$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{E}g'\succ h_{E}g'$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In words: if two acts imply different subacts over an event 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, but the same subact over the complement of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, the ranking of these acts will not depend on the common subset.
 This is very close to Expected Utility.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
P3-Event Monotonicity.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 non-null 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in Z$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{E}h\succ y_{E}h\iff x\succ y.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
P4.
 Weak comparative probability.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x,x',y,y'\in Z$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succ y,x'\succ y'$
\end_inset

, then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{E}h\succ y_{E}h\implies x'_{E}h\succ y'_{E}h.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When revealed the estimated probabilities of states these are independent
 from specific prizes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
P5- Non triviality.
 There exists 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\succ g$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
P6-Small event continuity.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f\succ g$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in Z$
\end_inset

 there exists a partition denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $(E_{1},\cdots,E_{n})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{Ei}f\succ g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\succ z_{Ei}g$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\cdots,n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a partition small enough that no small modification of an act will
 change the orders.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
A preference relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 satisfies P1-P6 if and only if it has a SEU representation.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is unique and 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is unique up to affine transformations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Ellsberg's Paradox and Ambiguity Aversion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose there is an urn with 
\begin_inset Formula $90$
\end_inset

 colored balls of which 
\begin_inset Formula $30$
\end_inset

 are known to be red and the remaining sixty are known to be either green
 or yellow.
 Thus the state space for bets on the color of a ball chosen from the urn
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\{R,G,Y\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be a bet that yields a dollar if a red ball is chosen and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 be a bet that yields a dollar if a green ball is chosen.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f'$
\end_inset

 be a bet that yields a dollar if a red or yellow ball is chosen, and let
 
\begin_inset Formula $g'$
\end_inset

 be a bet that yields a dollar if a green or yellow ball is chosen.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Tabular
