\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" leftline="true" rightline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
1
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
</row>
<row>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" bottomline="true" leftline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
g'
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" bottomline="true" leftline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
0
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" bottomline="true" leftline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
1
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" bottomline="true" leftline="true" rightline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
1
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
</row>
</lyxtabular>

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ellsberg observed that many people have preferences of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $f\succ g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g'\succ f'$
\end_inset

.
 This has been confirmed by careful experiments.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This violates Savage's P2.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To see this define 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 as a bet that always yields zero and 
\begin_inset Formula $h'$
\end_inset

 as a bet that always yields a dollar.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E=\{R,G\}$
\end_inset

 then using splicing 
\begin_inset Formula $f=f_{E}h$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g=g_{E}h$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f'=f_{E}h'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g'=g_{E}h'$
\end_inset

 , the axioms requires that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{E}h\succ g_{E}h\iff f_{E}h'\succ g_{E}h'.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Anscombe-Aumann
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we allow for observing also a bit of objective probabilities we can calibrate
 the subjective probabilities from the objective ones.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $S,Z$
\end_inset

 finite and consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}=(\Delta Z)^{S}$
\end_inset

, with preferences 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 This is a combination of horse race lotteries (with subjective probabilities)
 and roulette lotteries with objective probabilities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
For any 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 we define an act 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha f+(1-\alpha)g$
\end_inset

 so that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[\alpha f+(1-\alpha)g](s)=\alpha f(s)+(1-\alpha)g(s).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider the following axiom.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
A1-Independence.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g,h\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\succ g$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha f+(1-\alpha)h\succ\alpha g+(1-\alpha)h$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
A2-Mixture continuity.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g,h\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\alpha\in[0,1]|\alpha f+(1-\alpha)g\succeq h\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\alpha\in[0,1]|h\succeq\alpha f+(1-\alpha)g\}$
\end_inset

 are closed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
A3-Monotonicity.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(s)\succeq g(s)\forall s\implies f\succeq g$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
A4-Non-triviality.
 For some 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\succ g$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have the main representation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
A weak order 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

 satisfies A1-A4 if and only if there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $u:\Delta(Z)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\Delta(S)$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $U(f)=\sum_{s}u(f(s))p(s)$
\end_inset

 represents 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is unique, and 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is unique up to positive affine transformations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
First Models of Ambiguity Aversion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Choquet Expected Utility CEU
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The CEU model using the idea of a capacity to capture the degree of belief
 in an event.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula $v:2^{S}\to[0,1]$
\end_inset

 is a capacity if:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
1.
 
\begin_inset Formula $v(\emptyset)=0,v(S)=1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
2.
 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is monotone 
\begin_inset Formula $E\subseteq F\implies v(E)\leq v(F)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Recall the Ellsberg Paradox.
 The beliefs on 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\{R,G,B\}$
\end_inset

 can be represented by the following capacity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v(\{R\})=\frac{1}{3},v(\{R,G\})=v(\{R,B\})=\frac{1}{3},v(\{G\})=v(\{B\})=0,v(\{G,B\})=\frac{2}{3}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we evaluate a bet on event 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $v(E)$
\end_inset

 we get 
\begin_inset Formula $V(f)=\frac{1}{3}>0=V(g)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $V(g')=\frac{2}{3}>\frac{1}{3}=V(f')$
\end_inset

.
 So we can accommodate Ellberg's choices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The intuitive property that seems to relate ambiguity aversion in this example
 is superadditivity, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $v(A\cup B)\ge v(A)+v(B)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The property that captures ambiguity aversion is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A capacity 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is convex (supermodular) if and only if 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v(E\cup F)+v(E\cap F)\geq v(E)+v(F).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We define the core.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The core of a capacity 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
core(v):=\{p\in\Delta(S)|p(E)\geq v(E)\quad\forall E\subseteq S\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Every convex capacity has a non-empty core.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
We can create capacities by distorting probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $v(E)=\phi(p(E))$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=x_{1}E_{1}+\cdots+x_{n}E_{n}$
\end_inset

 for some partition 
\begin_inset Formula $\{E_{1},\cdots,E_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq x_{1}\leq x_{2}\leq\cdots\leq x_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}=0$
\end_inset

.
 The Choquet Integral of 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 with respect to a capacity 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int\xi dv=\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_{i}-x_{i-1})v(\cup_{j=1}^{i}E_{j}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Even more simple we can define 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}^{\xi,v}:=v(F_{i+1})-v(F_{i})$
\end_inset

, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $v(S)=\sum_{i=1}^{n}p_{i}^{\xi,v}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}^{\xi,v}\geq0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}\subseteq F_{i+1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}+p_{i-1}=v(F_{i+1})-v(F_{i})+v(F_{i})-v(F_{i-1})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the property of comonotonicity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Two acts 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi,\zeta$
\end_inset

 are comonotonic if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\not\exists s,s'\in S$
\end_inset

 s.t.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\xi(s)>\xi(s')\wedge\zeta(s)<\zeta(s').
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A function is comonotonic additive if and only if 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I(\xi+\zeta)=I(\xi)+I(\zeta).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is normalized, monotone, and satisfies comonotonic additivity if and only
 if there exists a Choquet capacity such that 
\begin_inset Formula $I(\xi)=\int\xi dv.$
\end_inset

 Moreover for convex capacities, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I(\xi)=min_{p\in core(v)}\int\xi dp.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The axiomatization is given by.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
C1-Comonotonic Independence.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g,h\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 pairwise comonotonic, and for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in(0,1)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\succ g\iff\alpha f+(1-\alpha)h\succ\alpha g+(1-\alpha)h.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also consider.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
C2-Uncertainty Aversion.
 Whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $f\sim g$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha f+(1-\alpha)g\succeq f$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider the main result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
A weak order 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 satisfies C1 (plus other technical axioms) iff there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $u:\Delta(Z)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and a capacity 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is represented by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\to\int u\circ fdv.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Moreover 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is unique up to affine transformations and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is unique.
 In addition, Axiom C2 holds iff 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is convex.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Ambiguity aversion, variational preferences.
 (MMR).
 Ecma 2006.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The representation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the Ascombe-Aumann framework, the preferences for which there are utility
 function 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 on outcomes and an ambiguity index 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 on the set of probabilities on the states of the world
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\succeq g\iff min_{p}\left(\int u(f)dp+c(p)\right)\geq min_{p}\left(\int u(g)dp+c(p)\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 represents the decision maker's (DM) risk attitudes while the index of
 ambiguity 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

, captures his ambiguity attitudes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This includes the multiple priors of Gilboa Schmeidler and the multiplier
 preferences of Hansen and Sargent.
 This provides a rigorous decision-theoretic foundation for the latter model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MULTIPLE PRIORS.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $V(f)=min_{p\in C}\int u(f)dp$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a given convex subset of the set of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 of all probabilities on states.
 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is interpreted as a set of priors held by agents, and ambiguity is reflected
 by the multiplicity of the priors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The underlying idea behind the expected utility is that agents hold a single
 belief.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under this hypothesis, all agents share the same probability distribution,
 and they are convinced this is the correct one.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This type of preferences allows agents to entertain different priors on
 the economy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The model of the world is just an approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Specifically, agents rank payoff profiles 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 according to the choice criterion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(f)=min_{p\in\Delta}\left(\int u(f)dp+\theta R(p||q)\right),
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\cdot||q):\Delta\rightarrow[0,\infty]$
\end_inset

 is the relative entropy with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 (see section 4.2 for the definition).
 Preferences represented by criterion (2) are called multiplier preferences.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The contribution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The authors provide a connection between ambiguity driven behavior and the
 multiplier preferences where rational expectations are replaced by a distributi
on of beliefs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Multiple priors representation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(f)=min_{p\in\Delta}\left(\int u(f)dp+\delta_{C}(p)\right),
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{C}:\Delta\rightarrow[0,\infty]$
\end_inset

 is the indicator function on 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 (in the sense of convex analysis)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta_{C}(p)=\begin{cases}
0 & if\quad p\in C\\
\infty & otherwise
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The indicator function in the convex analysis sense is convex on the simplex.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This also covers the case of multiplier preferences.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And finally the case of mean variance preferences of Markowitz and Tobin.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(f)=\int fdq-\frac{1}{2\theta}Var(f).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Theorem 24, MMR show that on the domain of monotonicity of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, the equality 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int fdq-\frac{1}{2\theta}Var(f)=min_{p\in\Delta}\left\{ \int fdp+\theta G(p||q)\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
holds.
 Where 
\begin_inset Formula $G(\cdot||q):\Delta\rightarrow[0,\infty]$
\end_inset

 is the relative Gini concentration index.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This preferences are probabilistic sophisticated when the cost function
 is symmetric if not they fail to be probabilistic sophisticated.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Probabilistic sophistication appears in both multiplier and mean variance
 preferences.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some recent psychological literature suggest that in this case the agent
 may behave as if he were playing against an informed opponent who might
 take advantage of this uncertainty and turn against him.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
SETUP.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 of states of the world, an algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 of subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 called events, and a set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 of consequences.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Acts.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f:S\mapsto X$
\end_inset

 which are 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma-$
\end_inset

measurable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- We denote 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{0}(\Sigma)$
\end_inset

 the set of all real-valued 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma-$
\end_inset

measurable simple functions.
 
\begin_inset Formula $u(f)\in B_{0}(\Sigma)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- 
\begin_inset Formula $u:X\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and we denote 
\begin_inset Formula $B(\Sigma)$
\end_inset

 the supnorm closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{0}(\Sigma)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, define 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 as the constant act 
\begin_inset Formula $x(s)=x$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{F},$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\Sigma$
\end_inset

 we denote 
\begin_inset Formula $xAf\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 the act that yields 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(s)$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $s\notin A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
-We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a convex subset of a vector space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 can be the set of all lotteries on a set of prizes 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(Z)=X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We model the decision maker's preferences on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 by a binary relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A certainty equivalent for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $f\sim x_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

