\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A binary relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 satisfies Axiom A.2' if and only if, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta\in(0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha f+(1-\alpha)x\succeq\alpha g+(1-\alpha)x
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\beta f+(1-\beta)y\succeq\beta g+(1-\beta)y.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gilboa Schmeidler's (1989) Axiom A.2.' has two kind of independence relations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(i) Independence with respect to mixing with a constant act.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(ii) Independence with respect to the weights using in such mixing.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{thm}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 be a binary relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 The following conditions are equivalent.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(i) The relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 satisfies Axioms A1-A6.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(ii) There exists a nonconstant affine function 
\begin_inset Formula $u:X\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and a grounded, convex and lower semicontinuous function 
\begin_inset Formula $c:\Delta\rightarrow[0,\infty]$
\end_inset

 such that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\succeq g\iff min_{p\in\Delta(\Sigma)}\left(\int u(f)dp+c(p)\right)\geq min_{p\in\Delta(\Sigma)}\left(\int u(g)dp+c(p)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 there is a (unique) minimal 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{*}:\Delta\rightarrow[0,\infty]$
\end_inset

 that satisfies (6) and is given by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c^{*}=sup_{f\in\mathcal{F}}\left(u(x_{f})-\int u(f)dp\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{thm}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the minimization of a convex lower semicontinuous function which
 is the most classical variational problem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Two pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $(u_{0},c_{o}^{*})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(u,c^{*})$
\end_inset

 represent the same variational preferences 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 as in Theorem 3 if an only if there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\alpha u_{0}+\beta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{*}=\alpha c_{0}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under unbounded 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{*}$
\end_inset

 is unique.
 
\end_layout

