\begin_layout Chapter
Axiomatic Foundations of Multiplier Preferences.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The representation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hansen and Sargent want to model situations where the decision maker does
 not have enough information to formulate a single probabilistic model and
 have full confidence in it, for example, when it is hard to statistically
 distinguish between similar probabilistic models.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(f)=min_{p}\int u(f)dp+\theta R(p||q)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\in(0,\infty]$
\end_inset

 is a parameter and 
\begin_inset Formula $R(p||q)$
\end_inset

 is the relative entropy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The consumer has a 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 prior, however she consider other close probabilities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Higher values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 correspond to more trust.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Multiplier preferences are a special case of variational preferences studied
 by Maccheroni, Marinacci and Rustichini 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(f)=min_{p}\int u(f)dp+c(p)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Is a very broad class, we want to pin down observational differences.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Contribution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main finding is that the sure-thing principle of Savage (imposed on
 the Anscombe-Aumman domain) characterized the class of multiplier preferences
 within the class of variational preferences (SOEU).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $V(f)=\int\phi(u(f))dq$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The multiplier preferences are the intersection of the variational preferences
 and the SOEU.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Importance, (i) it provides a set of testable predictions of the model that
 allows for its verification.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(ii) It provides a link between observed behavior of the agent and the parameter
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 (iii) Relation to Ellsberg paradox.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
PRELIMINARIES.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 states of the world.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The action taken before one 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S$
\end_inset

 occurs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 sigma-algebra of events in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The set of all finitely additive probabilities measures on 
\begin_inset Formula $(S,\Sigma)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(S)$
\end_inset

 and endowed with the weak 
\begin_inset Formula $*$
\end_inset

 topology.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A net 
\begin_inset Formula $\{p_{d}\}_{d\in D}$
\end_inset

 converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{d}(A)\rightarrow p(A)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The set of all countably additive probabilities is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{\sigma}(S)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The set of all measures absolutely continuous with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\Delta^{s}(S)$
\end_inset

 is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{\sigma}(q)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is the set of consequences.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 denotes simple probability distributions on 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Lotteries are elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Degenerate lotteries 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{z}$
\end_inset

, pays 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in Z$
\end_inset

 with probability 1.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\pi+(1-\alpha)\pi'$
\end_inset

 is a lottery that assigns 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\pi(z)+(1-\alpha)\pi(z)'$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in Z$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Acts.
 Mappings from 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

.
 Formally, a finite valued, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

-measurable function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:S\mapsto\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

, the set of all such acts is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(\Delta(Z))$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- If 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in\mathcal{F}(\Delta(Z))$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\Sigma$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{E}g(s)=f(s)$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{E}g(s)=g(s)$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $s\notin E$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha f+(1-\alpha)g$
\end_inset

 assigns a lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha f(s)+(1-\alpha)g(s)$
\end_inset

 for each state 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Choices 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f\succeq g$
\end_inset

 means that act 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is weakly preferred to 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- A functional 
\begin_inset Formula $V:\mathcal{F}(\Delta(Z))\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 represents 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in\mathcal{F}(\Delta(Z))$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\succeq g\iff V(f)\geq V(g)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Expected utility representation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(f)=\int_{S}(\sum_{z\in Z}u(z)f(s)(z))dq(s)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In each state of the world 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, the decision maker computes the expected utility of lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $f(s)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $u:\Delta(Z)\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\pi)=\sum_{z\in Z}u(z)\pi(z)$
\end_inset

 then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $V(f)=\int_{S}u(f(s))dq(s)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
SOURCES OF UNCERTAINTY.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Subjective: 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 the states have no objective probability.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Objective: Given an state 
\begin_inset Formula $f(s)$
\end_inset

 is an objective lottery.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Purely objective lotteries.
 Acts which pay the same lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\in\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 irrespective of the state.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Purely subjective acts.
 That is acts, that in each state of the world pay off a degenerate 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{z}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in Z$
\end_inset

 (which depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 be the set of purely objective lotteries.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Given a 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\Delta(S)$
\end_inset

, each purely subjective act 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 induces a purely objective lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{f}\in\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{f}(z)=q(f^{-1}(z))$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in Z$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- OBSERVATION 1: An EU DM has the same attitude toward objective lotteries
 and toward subjective acts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In particular, any purely subjective act 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is indifferent to the objective lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{f}$
\end_inset

 that it induces.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- ELLSBERG PARADOX.
 People prefer risk instead of ambiguity.
 Example here.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ambiguity aversion cannot be reconciled with EU model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Two approaches: (i) Introduce instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

, with some other measure of belief that captures the decision maker lack
 of information about the source.
 Choquet, maxmin model, variational preferences.
 (ii) The other approach is to keep 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 but to introduce another parameter that captures the higher aversion toward
 variability of the source of uncertainty.
 
\end_layout

