\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{thm}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 has at least three disjoint nonnull events, then Axioms A1-A6, A8 and P2
 are necessary and sufficient for 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 to have a multiplier representation (2).
 Moreover, in this case, two triples 
\begin_inset Formula $(\theta',u',q')$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\theta'',u'',q'')$
\end_inset

 represent the same multiplier preference 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 if an only if 
\begin_inset Formula $q'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q''$
\end_inset

 are identical, and there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u'=\alpha u''+\beta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta'=\alpha\theta''$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{thm}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proof.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The variational formula.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For any bounded and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma-$
\end_inset

measurable function 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi:S\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\Delta^{\sigma}(S)$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
min_{p\in\Delta(S)}\int_{S}\xi dp+\theta R(p||q)=\phi_{\theta}^{-1}\left(\int_{S}\phi_{\theta}\circ\xi dq\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then we have two variational formulas are ordinally equivalent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
min_{p\in\Delta(S)}\int_{S}u(f(s))dp+\theta R(p||q)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and the 
\begin_inset Formula $SOEU$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{S}\phi_{\theta}(u(f(s)))dq(s)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This establish the necessity of the MMR axioms and P2 axiom of Savage.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The sufficiency argument relies on the fact that the MMR axioms guarantee
 the existence of an affine utility 
\begin_inset Formula $u:\Delta(Z)\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and a functional 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 that maps utility-valued acts to reals, such that the functional 
\begin_inset Formula $f\rightarrow I(u(f))$
\end_inset

 represents the preferences.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MMR showed that the functional 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 has the translation invariance property 
\begin_inset Formula $I(u\circ f+k)=I(u\circ f)+k$
\end_inset

 for any act 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and any act 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and any 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, Axiom P2 together with the MMR axioms implies that the
 preferences have a SOEU representation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{S}\phi(u(f(s))dq(s)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for some strictly increasing function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Axioms A3 and A5 imply that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is continuous and concave, and Axiom A8 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is countably additive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This representation, together with translation invariance, implies that
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{S}\phi(u(f(s))dq(s)\geq\int_{S}\phi(u(g(s)))dq(s)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
if and only if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{S}\phi(u(f(s))+k)dq(s)\geq\int_{S}\phi(u(g(s))+k)dq(s)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which by uniqueness of the SOEU representation implies that there exists
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(k)>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta(k)\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x+k)=\alpha(k)\phi(x)+\beta(k)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,k\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a generalized Pexider equation, whose only solutions are 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{\theta}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\in(0,\infty]$
\end_inset

 which establishes the sufficiency of the axioms.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Instead of relying on the assumption of objective risk, there is also an
 axiomatization when there is two subjective sources of uncertainty.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Subjective Sources of Uncertainty.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume that the state space has a product structure 
\begin_inset Formula $S=S_{a}\times S_{b}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are two separate issues, or sources of uncertainty, toward which the decision
 maker may have different attitudes.
 In comparison with the Ascombe-Aumann framework, where objective risk is
 one of the sources, here both sources are subjective.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}_{a}$
\end_inset

 be the sigma algebra of subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{a}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}_{b}$
\end_inset

 be a sigma algebra of subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{b}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{a}$
\end_inset

 be the sigma algebra of sets of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $A\times S_{b}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{A}_{a}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{b}$
\end_inset

 be the sigma algebra of sets of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{a}\times B$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $B\in\mathcal{A}_{b}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 be the sigma algebra generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{a}\cup\Sigma_{b}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(Z)$
\end_inset

 be the set of all simple 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma-$
\end_inset

measurable acts 
\begin_inset Formula $f:S\rightarrow Z$
\end_inset

, moreover, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{a}(Z)$
\end_inset

 be the set of acts that are 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{a}$
\end_inset

 measurable and likewise 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{b}(Z)$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{U}$
\end_inset

 denote the set of 
\begin_inset Formula $u(Z)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This representation combines a general second order subjective representation
 with weak independence axiom of MMR to get the representation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Ambiguity and Trade
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Subjective Beliefs and Ex Ante Trade.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Contribution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using a generalized framework of convex preferences.
 The authors RSS are able to express in a unified way most models of ambiguity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
-In the case of Multiple priors, purely speculative trade occurs when agents
 hold no priors in common.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Full insurance is Pareto optimal if and only if agents have at least one
 prior in common.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Convex Choquet model is included, smooth second-order prior model, Second-orde
r expected utility the confidence preferences, the multiplier preferences
 and the variational preferences of MMR.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- A notion of subjective beliefs in markets is connected with axiomatic
 approaches to subjective beliefs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Beliefs and convex preferences.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a finite set of states of the world.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The set of consequences in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}_{+}$
\end_inset

 which we interpret as monetary payoffs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The set of acts is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}=\mathbb{R}_{+}^{S}$
\end_inset

 with the natural topology.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Acts denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g,h\mathcal{\in F}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(s)$
\end_inset

 is the payoff when the state is 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Constant act 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}_{+}$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is paid each state of the world.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is a binary relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is a convex preference relation if it satisfies the following axioms:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ax}{G.1.}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Preference.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is complete and transitive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ax}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ax}{G.2.}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Continuity.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

, the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\{g\in\mathcal{F}|g\succeq f\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{g\in\mathcal{F}|f\succeq g\}$
\end_inset

 are closed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ax}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ax}{G.3.}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Monotonicity.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(s)>g(s)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f\succ g$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ax}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ax}{G.4.}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Convexity.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{g\in\mathcal{F}|g\succeq f\}$
\end_inset

 is convex.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ax}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
REPRESENTATION.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is represented by a function 
\begin_inset Formula $V:\mathcal{F}\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 that is continuous, increasing, and quasiconcave.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Supporting hyperplanes and Beliefs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Decision Theory one can identify the subjective probabilities using the
 odds that a consumer is willing to make small bets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Yaari (69) identified subjective probability with a hyperplane that supports
 the upper contour set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When there is no differentiabilities they use the set of all normalized
 supporting hyperplanes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Subjective Beliefs.
 The set of subjective beliefs at an act 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi(f):=\{p\in\Delta S|p\cdot g\geq p\cdot f\quad\forall g\succeq f\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since they are beliefs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi(f):=\{p\in\Delta S|E_{p}g\geq E_{p}f\quad\forall g\succeq f\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 convex preference, then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(f)$
\end_inset

 is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- nonempty 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
-compact 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
-convex
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And is equal to the set of normalized support to the upper contour set of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

