\begin_layout Standard
The following is the key result.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (9) If the aggregate endowment is constant across states and 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq_{i}$
\end_inset

 satisfies Axioms 1-7 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, then the following statements are equivalent:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(i) There exists an interior full insurance Pareto optimal allocation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(ii) Any Pareto optimal allocation is a full insurance allocation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(iii) Every full insurance allocation is Pareto optimal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(iv) 
\begin_inset Formula $\cap_{i}\pi_{i}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(i) 
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

 (iv)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $x=(x_{1},\cdots,x_{m})$
\end_inset

 is an interior full insurance allocation that is Pareto optimal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By the second welfare theorem there exist 
\begin_inset Formula $p\neq0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 supports the allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, that is, such that for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot f\geq p\cdot x_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f\succeq_{i}x_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 By monotonicity, 
\begin_inset Formula $p>0$
\end_inset

 so after normalizing we take 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\Delta S$
\end_inset

.
 By definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\pi_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\cap_{i}\pi_{i}\neq\emptyset.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(iv)
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

(ii)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Take 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\cap_{i}\pi_{i}$
\end_inset

 and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a Pareto optimal allocation such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

 is non constant for some 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}=E_{p}f_{i}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 By strict monotonicity, 
\begin_inset Formula $p>>0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and by strict convexity, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}\succ_{j}f_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $x=(x_{1},\cdots,x_{m})$
\end_inset

 is feasible, and Pareto dominates 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 which is a contradiction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

 (iii) Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a full insurance allocation that is not Pareto optimal.
 Then there is a Pareto optimal allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 that Pareto dominates 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 By (ii), 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 must be a full insurance allocation which is a contradiction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(iii) 
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

 (i) The allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $(\frac{1}{m}e,\cdots,\frac{1}{m}e)$
\end_inset

 is an interior full insurance allocation.
 By (iii) it is Pareto optimal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main contribution is not establishing the link between efficiency and
 notions of common prior per se, but illustrating that these results are
 a simple consequence of the welfare theorems linking Pareto optimality
 to the existence of linear functional providing common support to agent's
 preferred sets, coupled with the particular form these supports take for
 various classes of preferences.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For multiplier preferences (iv) means that the reference measures coincide.
 There is a common prior.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Coarse Competitive Equilibrium and Extreme Prices.
 (Gul, Persendorfer, Strzalecki 2014)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Contribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
New notion of Coarse Competitive Equilibrium CCE, to study household inability
 to tailor their consumption to the state of the economy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
They motivate the model by attention, memory and complexity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The result is that in comparison with competitive equilibrium the allocation
 are riskier and have more extreme prices both for consumption and assets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Cognitive ability can produce market data that is usually attributed to
 heightened degrees of risk aversion.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Motivation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Many of the empirical puzzles in macroeconomics and finance arise from researche
r inability to reconcile the levels of risk aversion implied by the equilibrium
 models with the levels that are observed in other contexts or are reasonable
 a priori.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Equity premium puzzle is the observation that the stock returns are too
 large given reasonable levels of risk aversion and observed variability
 of aggregate consumption and dividends.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Home bias, refers to the comparatively much higher risk aversion that investor
 exhibit toward foreign assets by forgoing the diversification opportunities
 that the markets offer.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The model with cognitive limitation is equivalent to an economy without
 limitations but with higher risk.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Households must tailor actions to circumstances.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When circumstances are history of past events then there is a memory cost.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When circumstances are future contingencies there is a complexity cost.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When circumstances are a current variable they interpret this as costly
 information processing or communication cost.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Circumstances are with the realized price and action with consumption level.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
CCE in a Static Economy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
-There is a unit mass of households with identical utility functions but
 different stochastic endowments of the single physical good.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Aggregate endowment depends on the realization of the state 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $i\in N=\{1,\cdots,n\}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}$
\end_inset

 denote the probability of the uncertain state 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
-
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 the aggregate endowment in state 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- 
\begin_inset Formula $K(s)$
\end_inset

 the finite support of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- 
\begin_inset Formula $a=max_{s}K(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b=min_{s}K(s)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $0<b<a$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- 
\begin_inset Formula $|K(s)|$
\end_inset

 is the number of distinct endowment realizations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Consumption plan is a vector in 
\begin_inset Formula $C=\mathbb{R}_{+}^{n}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The household's utility of the consumption plan 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U(c)=\sum_{i\in N}u(c_{i})\pi_{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is any strictly concave CRRA utility index.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho>0$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(c_{i})=\begin{cases}
c_{i}^{1-\rho}/(1-\rho) & if\quad\rho\neq1\\
lnc_{i} & if\quad\rho=1
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- In CCE households are restricted to coarse consumption plans, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

plans with at most 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 distinct consumption levels
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 In the non trivial case 
\begin_inset Formula $1<k<|K(s)|$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (1) The consumption plan 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in C$
\end_inset

 is coarse if 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $|\{c_{i}|i\in N\}|\leq k$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Let 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{k}$
\end_inset

 be the set of all coarse consumption plans.
 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{k}\subset C_{k+1}$
\end_inset

.
 And 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{k}$
\end_inset

 is not convex since 
\begin_inset Formula $c,c'\in C_{k}$
\end_inset

 any convex combination requires more than 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 consumption goods.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- This implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $k=2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $|K(s)|=4$
\end_inset

 some households will consume the same amount in the first two states while
 others consume the same quantities in the last two states.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- An element 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in the simplex 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(N)$
\end_inset

 is a (normalized) price.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Endowment 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in\mathbb{R}_{+}^{N}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- At price 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, the wealth of the household 
\begin_inset Formula $w=p\cdot\omega=\sum_{i\in N}\omega_{i}\cdot p_{i}$
\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The household's budget set is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
