\begin_inset Formula $\mu(c)$
\end_inset

 represents the fraction of households who choose plan 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in C$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The coarse consumption plan 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in B_{k}(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is optimal at prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $w>0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $U(c)\geq U(c')$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $c'\in B_{k}(p,w)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The assumption of CRRA, optimal consumption plans are homogeneous in the
 household wealth!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- A coarse consumption 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is optimal for a household with wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 and prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 if an only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{p\cdot s}{w}c$
\end_inset

 is optimal for the representative agent at price 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Therefore, aggregate demand is independent of the wealth distribution
 and so are CCE equilibrium prices.
 
\end_layout

