\begin_layout Section
Consumption Risk and Price Variation in a CCE.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 CCE has greater consumption risk.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\mathbb{R}^{N}$
\end_inset

, we let 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{z}$
\end_inset

 denote the cumulative distribution of a random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $F_{z}(x)=\sum_{i:z_{i}\leq x}\pi_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{s}$
\end_inset

 is the cdf of the endowment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{c}$
\end_inset

 is the cdf of consumption associated with the plan 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is the cdf of consumption given allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $G_{\mu}(x)=\sum_{c}F_{c}(x)\cdot\mu(c)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Random consumption is as the result of a two stage lottery.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 The first stage reveals the state 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in N$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Second stage reveals the consumption in state 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $k<|K(s)|$
\end_inset

 consuming the endowment in every state is not feasible and there are 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in K(\mu)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}\neq s_{i}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in N$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moreover 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}\geq\sigma_{i}(\mu)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is feasible and hence the expected value of consumption in state 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is less than equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 (the consumption in standard CE).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- This implies that consumption SCE second order stochastically dominates
 CCE consumption and welfare (mean utility).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- SUMMARY, since 
\begin_inset Formula $s\notin C_{k}$
\end_inset

 ensures that the representative household bears greater risk in a CCE than
 in SCE.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Another implication: When different households have different endowments
 a CCE may result in less income inequality than a SCE.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Convergent economies and extreme prices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second feature is that for any fixed range of endowments 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

 the equilibrium price 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\Delta(N)$
\end_inset

 in a CCE can be arbitrarily large or arbitrarily close to zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{n}$
\end_inset

 be a pure endowment economy with 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq k+1$
\end_inset

 states and order 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}<s_{j}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $i<j$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

[6] A sequence of economies 
\begin_inset Formula $\{E^{n}\}=\{(u,k,\pi^{n},s^{n})\}$
\end_inset

 is convergent if 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{n}$
\end_inset

 converges in distribution to a random variable with a continuous and strictly
 positive density on 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The price kernel
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\kappa_{i}^{n}=\frac{p_{i}^{n}}{\pi_{i}^{n}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A CCE sequence is 
\begin_inset Formula $\{p^{n},\kappa^{n}\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Pr(X\in A):\sum_{i:X_{i}\in A}\pi_{i}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For any compact set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, every sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x^{n}\}\subset X$
\end_inset

 has a convergent subsequence.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{thm}
\end_layout

\end_inset

[3] For any CCE sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(p^{n},\kappa^{n})\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

, (i) 
\begin_inset Formula $limp_{1}^{n}>0$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $p\geq1$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $limPr(\kappa^{n}>K)>0$
\end_inset

 and (ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $limPr(\kappa^{n}<\epsilon)>0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $p>1$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $limPr(p^{n}=0)>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{thm}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
CCE in a Dynamic Economy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is the set of states, 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in N$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- A 
\begin_inset Formula $t-$
\end_inset

period history 
\begin_inset Formula $h=(i_{1},\cdots,i_{t})\in N^{t}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- 
\begin_inset Formula $hi=(h,i)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{t}$
\end_inset

 the set of all t-period histories and 
\begin_inset Formula $H=\cup_{t\geq1}N^{t}$
\end_inset

 the set of all histories.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Terminal node 
\begin_inset Formula $j(h)=i_{t}$
\end_inset

 for history 
\begin_inset Formula $h=(i_{1},\cdots,i_{t})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{i}^{t}=\{h\in N^{t}:j(h)=i\}$
\end_inset

 the set of all 
\begin_inset Formula $t-$
\end_inset

period histories that end in 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- A matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

, describes the evolution of the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{it}$
\end_inset

 is the probability that the state at date 
\begin_inset Formula $t+1$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 given that it is 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 on date 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 has a stationary distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi=\pi\cdot\Phi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The probability of history 
\begin_inset Formula $h=(i_{1},\cdots,i_{t})\in H^{t}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{h}=\pi_{i1}\phi_{i1,i2}\cdots\phi_{it-1,it}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- A function 
\begin_inset Formula $d\in\mathbb{R}_{+}^{H}$
\end_inset

 is a dynamic consumption plan and 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is the set of all consumption plans.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The consumption plan 
\begin_inset Formula $d\in D$
\end_inset

 is coarse if 
\begin_inset Formula $|\{d_{h}|h\in H\}|\leq k$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{k}$
\end_inset

 be the set of all coarse consumption plans.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- During their entire lifetime the household has at most 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 different levels of consumption.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The household's utility from the consumption plan 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $V(d)=(1-\beta)\sum_{t\geq1}\sum_{h\in N^{t}}u(d_{h})\beta^{t-1}\lambda_{h}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is the discount factor.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The economy 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{*}=(u,\beta,k,\pi,s,\Phi)$
\end_inset

 is a dynamic economy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- ALLOCATION is a probability distribution on 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in\Delta(D)$
\end_inset

 is Coarse if the support is contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Feasible: 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{h}(v)=\sum_{d\in K(v)}d_{h}\cdot v(d)\leq s_{j(h)}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in M(D_{k})$
\end_inset

 is the set of feasible allocation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Dynamic price
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{H}q_{h}=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\mathbb{R}_{+}^{H}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Household budget's 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{k}^{*}=\{d\in D_{k}:\sum_{h\in H}q_{h}|d_{h}-s_{j(h)}|\leq0\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Coarse consumption plan 
\begin_inset Formula $d\in B_{k}(p)$
\end_inset

 is optimal at prices 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $V(d)\geq V(d')$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $d'\in B_{k}(q)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The price allocation pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(q,v)$
\end_inset

 is a CCE of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 if (i) 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is feasible for 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and (ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $v(d)>0$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is optimal at prices 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equivalence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fix 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{*}=\{u,\beta,k,\pi,s,\Phi\}$
\end_inset

 and consider 
\begin_inset Formula $E=(u,k,\pi,s)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
the same utility and coarseness constraint.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Initial endowment chosen in basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is the stationary distribution 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{h\in H_{i}^{t}}\lambda_{h}=\pi_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\geq1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-\beta)\sum_{t}\sum_{h\in H_{i}^{t}}\beta^{t-1}\lambda_{h}=\pi_{i}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dynamic economy can be thought of as a version of the static economy
 in which each state 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 split into many identical states corresponding to the branches of the event
 tree that end with 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{thm}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (i) If 
\begin_inset Formula $(p,\mu)$
\end_inset

 is a CCE of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(T_{2}(p),T_{3}(\mu))$
\end_inset

 is a CCE of 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 (ii) If 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is a CCE allocation for 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{*}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in\Delta(D)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{3}^{-1}(v)$
\end_inset

 is a CCe allocation for 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 
