\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Bubble Game.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The contribution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
They propose a bubble game that involves a sequential trading of an asset
 commonly known to be valueless.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
No trader is sure to be last in the market sequence, the game allows for
 a bubble at the Nash equilibrium when there is no cap on the maximum price.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We run experiments both with and without a price cap.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Structural estimation of behavioral game theory suggests that quantal responses
 and analogy-based expectations are important drivers of speculations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Bubbles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
DEFINITION.
 Value of an asset.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this paper we define the fundamental value of an asset as the price at
 which agents would be ready to buy the asset given that they cannot resell
 it.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
KEY DESIGN.
 They control for the number of trading opportunities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- A sequential market for an asset that generates no cash flow (announced
 publicly to participants).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Traders do not know where they stand in the market sequence and cannot
 observe past past trader's actions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The price proposed to the first trader in the market sequence is random
 and the subsequent price path is exogenous.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Traders have limited liabilities and are financed by outside financiers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- At each point in the sequence the trader can buy or not by in the incoming
 offer at the proposed price.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- If someone declines the offer, the game ends and the seller at each point
 is stuck with the asset.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
THE PRICE CAP.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Treatment: Price cap, Control no Price cap.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under Nash Equilibrium reasoning, when there is a price cap only irrational
 bubbles can form.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By backward induction no one will buy the asset that is worthless.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Key assumption, all agents are rational and rationality is common knowledge.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
ANOTHER KEY PART OF THE DESIGN.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By increasing the level of the cap, one increases the number of steps of
 iterated reasoning needed to rule out the bubble.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The lack of higher order of rationality affects speculative bubbles.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Bounded rationality has an effect on the formation of an speculative bubble.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- When the price cap is infinite bubbles can be rational because no trader
 is ever sure to be the last in the market sequence.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
SIMULATING INFINITE TRADE IN THE LAB.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Difficulty, experimental analysis of rational bubbles is difficult because
 extant theories in which bubbles are common knowledge involve infinite
 trading opportunities and infinite losses.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Solution.
 There is a finite number of trades and the potentially infinite losses
 are concentrated in the hands of outside financiers who are consequently
 not part of the experiment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
SEVERAL TREATMENTS.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
LEVEL 1.
 Price cap vs.
 No price cap.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Level 2.
 Level of the price cap.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
RESULTS.
 Bubbles form even if ruled out by backward induction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Bubbles arise whether there is price cap or not.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Bubbles thus form even if ruled out by backward induction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The propensity of a subject to enter a bubble increases with the distance
 between the offered price and the maximum price.
 (Snow-ball effect).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There is a snow-ball effect, and they show that it is related to a higher
 probability not to be the last and to a higher number of iterated steps
 of reasoning.
 (Identified by the different level of caps, the levels of reasoning).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Participants just play one shot game.
 And they are under one treatment.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
EXPLANATIONS OF RESULTS.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Cognitive hierarchies.
 CH.
 This model considers that players underestimate other agent's sophistication.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Quantal response equilibrium.
 QRE.
 It features players who correctly anticipate other's mistakes.
 Strategic uncertainty and how it propagates across the nodes of the game.
 (Example centipede).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Finally, it might be difficult form beliefs about the likelihood of speculation
 at each possible transaction price.
 So players may simplify the problem by assuming that this likelihood is
 the same across various transactions.
 Analogy based expectation equilibrium ABEE.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MAIN STYLIZED FACTS.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The existence of bubbles even when there is no cap.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The presence of snowball effect.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
EFFECTS.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The heterogeneous QRE is the model that gives the best fit to the data.
 HQRE takes into account the fact that payoff responsiveness varies across
 the subjects.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
BOTTOM LINE.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main message is that both stochastic choice and analogy classes are
 important drivers of speculation in the bubble game.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
CONTRIBUTION II.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(i) Preferences for risk cannot explain the behavior to buy at maximum price.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(ii) One can observe the behavior at different level of steps.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Bubble Game.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- common value 0
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Three traders in the market.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Trading proceeds sequentially.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Each trader has position 1, 2, 3 with 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\frac{1}{3}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Traders are not told the position in the market, but do observe the price.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Prices are exogenously fixed and are powers of 10.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The first offerer is random and fixed in 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{1}=10^{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 follows a geometric distribution of parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}(n=j)=\frac{1^{j+1}}{2}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $j\in\{01,2,\cdots\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The probability of being last is zero if 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $n=10$
\end_inset

 else it is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{4}{7}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The probabilities of being first, second or third conditional on each
 price, computed using Bayes rule are given to the participants in the instructi
ons.
 !
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- If trader 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 buys, he can make an offer 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{t+1}=10P_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Players play simultaneously.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Once 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{1}$
\end_inset

 has been randomly determined, the first, the second, and third traders
 are simultaneously offered prices of 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{1},P_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{3}$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 If they decide to buy they automatically propose to resell the asset.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Each trader is endowed with one unit capital.
 Additional capital may be required so as to buy the asset at price 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{t}>1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The additional capital (
\begin_inset Formula $P_{t}-1$
\end_inset

) is provided by an outside financier.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- With a proportion equal to the capital invested, the experimenter and
 the subject share the profits.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{P_{t}}$
\end_inset

 for the trader and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{P_{t}-1}{P_{t}}$
\end_inset

 for the financier.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The feature of external financing is the presence of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

limited liability
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that is the subject of the experiment may loose only 1 dollar.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The potentially infinite losses or gains are incurred by the financiers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Individual rationality for 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 IR
\begin_inset Formula $_{j}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[1-\mathbb{P}(last)]\times\mathbb{P}(next\quad trader\quad buys)\times U_{j}(10)+
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
+\{[1-\mathbb{P}(last)]\times\mathbb{P}(next\quad trader\quad does\quad not\quad buy)+\mathbb{P}(last)\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\times U_{j}(0)\geq U_{j}(1),
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The Treatment, the cap is introduced using a cap in the first price equal
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $K=10^{k}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\{01,2,\cdots,\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- With only three traders, the cap 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 on the first price translates into a cap of 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{k+2}=100K$
\end_inset

 on the the highest potential price in the bubble game.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
BAYESIAN EQUILIBRIUM.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is finite, upon being offered a price of 
\begin_inset Formula $100K$
\end_inset

, the agent understands that he is the last in the market sequence.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Consequently his IR3 is violated and he does not buy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Anticipating the refusal, agents who are also offered less price will
 refuse to buy even if they are not sure of being the last in the market.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- At a certain price 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq P\leq100K$
\end_inset

 the required number of iterated steps of reasoning is 
\begin_inset Formula $log_{10}(\frac{100K}{P})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Treatments 
\begin_inset Formula $K\in\{$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $1,100,10000\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Full rationality may give rise to a bubble for certain concave utility
 index.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Neither infinite trading horizon nor infinite trading speed is necessary
 for common knowledge rational bubbles to exist.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- No trader is ever sure to be the last in the sequence.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For several financiers, fueling the bubble may be rational.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[1-\mathbb{P}(last)]\mathbb{P}(next\quad trader\quad buys)U_{f}(W+10P_{t}-10)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
+\{[1-\mathbb{P}(last)]\times\mathbb{P}(next\quad trader\quad does\quad not\quad buy)+\mathbb{P}(last)\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\times U_{f}(W-P_{t}+1)\geq U_{f}(W)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If all financiers expect all traders to speculate there exists a function
 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{f}(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 for which the (IRf) condition holds.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Experiment protocol.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- 234 individuals.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Subjects are junior and senior undergraduate in business administration
 at University of Toulouse.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- One session with 5 euro showup fee.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Each session includes only one replication of the trading game.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Subject risk aversion is measured.
 This is done in a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

frame
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that is similar to the experimental setting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename C:/Users/pegasuspc/Documents/Browhphd/field_exams/consumer_theory/papers/bubblegame/table_1.emf
	lyxscale 300

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The minimum, median and maximum and average gains in the experiment are
 respectively 0, 1, 10 and 3.35 euros not including the showup fee.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The instructions for the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $K=10000$
\end_inset

 are in appendix B.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Behavioral Game Theory Prediction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Subjective Quantal Response Equilibrium.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According SQRE logic, an agent's payoff responsiveness, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i,s}$
\end_inset

 depends on his type 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and on his level of sophistication, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
SQRE then involves a stochastic choice model whereby the agent's propensity
 to choose an action has a logistic form that depends on the expected payoff
 of his action given his information and on his payoff responsiveness.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The expected payoff of buying the asset condition on buying the asset
 in denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i,s}(B|P)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The expected payoff from not buying the asset is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\emptyset}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}_{is}(B|P)=\frac{e^{\lambda_{i,s}u_{i,s}(B|P)}}{e^{\lambda_{i,s}u_{i,s}(B|P)}+e^{\lambda_{i,s}u_{\emptyset}}}$
\end_inset

, the probability of agent 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 to buy the asset after being offered at price 
\begin_inset Formula $P.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i,s}=\lambda_{i}+\gamma s$
\end_inset

 where is common knowledge that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

 is uniformly distributed on the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[\Lambda-\frac{\epsilon}{2},\Lambda+\frac{\epsilon}{2}]$
\end_inset

 and where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 represents the sensitivity of an agent's payoff responsiveness to his level
 of sophistication.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The level of sophistication 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is Poisson with density 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- A player with sophistication 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 cannot imagine that any other player has sophistication 
\begin_inset Formula $s-\theta.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The players truncated distribution about the fraction of 
\begin_inset Formula $h-$
\end_inset

level players is thus 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{s}(h)=\frac{f(h)}{\sum_{i=0}^{max(s-\theta,0)}f(i)}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 denote the average level of sophistication.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- We can write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{i,s}(B|P)=10[1-\mathbb{P}(last|P)]\sum_{h=0}^{max(s-\theta,0)}g_{s}(h)\mathbb{P}_{i;',h}(B|10P).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The parameters are five: 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda,$
\end_inset

 responsiveness, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 the average level of sophistication, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 the imagination parameter, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 the sensitivity of payoff responsiveness to sophistication.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- SQRE is useful to incorporate the notion of skill.
 Skill is captured by the payoff 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i,s}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i,s}$
\end_inset

 the more responsive the player is to payoffs and the better he perceives
 other player's skills.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The player may mis-perceive the skill distribution but condition on the
 skill level, he holds correct beliefs on the choice probabilities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- SQRE nests the Cognitive Hierarchies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- CH believe that all other agents sophistication is lower than theirs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- HQRE heterogeneity is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

, that do not for sure the level responsiveness of another agent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 or imagination, can measure the extent that a player underestimates its
 contender.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- 
\end_layout

